# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: malta
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The plot is believed to have been instigated by Mustafa, Pasha of Rhodes, an Ottoman official who had been captured following a revolt by Christian slaves on his galley *Lupa* in January 1748.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] He was enslaved upon the galley's arrival in Malta in February 1748, but he was given comfortable living quarters due to his high rank and he was formally freed in May 1749 following French intervention due to the Franco-Ottoman alliance.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The revolt involved a planned takeover of the Grand Master's Palace and other key locations in Valletta and Birgu, an uprising among slaves on board the Hospitaller galley squadron, and naval support from the Barbary states and the Ottomans.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The uprising was to take place on 29 June 1749, but plans leaked to the Hospitallers in advance, and the plot was foiled before it could be implemented.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Some 150 people – including Muslim slaves and Christian neophytes – were arrested and interrogated under torture in the subsequent trials.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] 35 were executed between July and October 1749, while 3 others died in custody and 72 were condemned to the galleys.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Due to French influence, Mustafa was not punished for his role in the plot, and he returned to Constantinople in 1751.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] During the mid-18th century, Malta was ruled by the Knights Hospitaller.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] At the time slavery was practiced throughout both Christian and Muslim-ruled territories around the Mediterranean, and the majority of slaves on the Maltese Islands were Muslim men who had been captured at sea by the Hospitaller fleet or by Malta-based corsairs.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Some were forced to work as galley slaves while others worked on land as labourers and had a variety of duties ranging from manufacturing to domestic roles.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The slave population typically stood at around 2,000 people, although some sources claim that in 1749 there were up to 9,300 slaves in Malta.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The proportion of slaves was higher in Malta's main urban area around the Grand Harbour, where slaves constituted about 10% of the population.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Although there were laws which prevented slaves from interacting with the Maltese people, these were not regularly enforced and some slaves worked as merchants and sold wares in the streets and squares of the capital Valletta.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] At night publicly-owned slaves were confined to prisons known as bagnios: the main one was the Gran Prigione in Valletta, while similar prisons existed in the cities of Birgu and Senglea.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Slaves were allowed freedom of religion and were able to gather for prayers.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Although large-scale slave revolts were a rare occurrence, several successful escapes and unsuccessful escape attempts by Muslim slaves in Malta are known to have occurred prior to 1749.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] These include a 1531 attempt to take Fort St.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Angelo, uprisings on the galleys *Caterinetta* and *San Giacomo* in 1548 and 1557 respectively, and a 1596 mass escape attempt from Valletta.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] In 1609, suspicions were raised that slaves were planning to poison bread in order to facilitate a Muslim invasion of Malta, and in 1627 slaves were accused of plotting to poison bread at the Grand Master's Palace in order to assassinate Grand Master Antoine de Paule.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] In January 1748, Hungarian, Georgian and Maltese slaves on board the Ottoman galley *Lupa* revolted, massacred most of the crew, commandeered the ship and imprisoned the remaining Ottomans on board, including Mustafa, the former Pasha of Rhodes.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Among the planners of this revolt was Cara Mehmed, a Muslim slave who had been granted freedom by Mustafa's father but who had continued to be treated as a slave by Mustafa.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The rebel slaves sailed the ship to Malta, where they arrived in the beginning of February.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Mustafa was subsequently enslaved, although he received special treatment due to his high rank, initially being accommodated in comfortable living quarters at Fort Saint Elmo before being moved to a house in Floriana in July 1748.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] On 5 May 1749, Mustafa was freed from slavery following French efforts to procure his release as a result of the Franco-Ottoman alliance.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] He refused offers of leave the island upon his release, claiming that he wanted instructions from the Ottoman sultanate before doing so.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Cara Mehmed also remained in Malta, and in June 1748 he was baptised as a Catholic and was given the baptismal name of Giovanni Battista.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] He married a Maltese woman and obtained employment as a liveried groom to Grand Master Manuel Pinto da Fonseca.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] At the time of his capture, Mustafa's governorship of Rhodes had just ended and he had been expecting to be appointed to another post.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] He is believed to have been motivated to attempt to take over Malta by instigating a slave revolt in order to redeem his honour and regain favour with the Ottoman sultan.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Mustafa orchestrated the plot through the use of other people as intermediaries, and he made efforts to ensure that he would not be blamed personally if the plot was discovered prematurely.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Mustafa was able to discuss the planned revolt with other conspirators while he was living in Floriana.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] At least two meetings are known to have taken place; Mustafa was personally present in the second one, and all those involved took an oath of secrecy.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The plotters included Pinto's valet Imselleti, Rais Hassan, Mishud, the *papasso* Haec Musa, and Giovanni Battista (formerly Cara Mehmed).
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The revolt was planned to take place on the day of the feast of Saints Peter and Paul (Maltese: *L-Imnarja*).
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] At the time, Valletta was expected to be quiet since many people would be celebrating the festivities in the inland city of Mdina and the nearby Boschetto, while the Hospitaller naval squadron would be at sea.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Although this meant that the galley slaves could not be part of the land-based revolt, there would be fewer soldiers and sailors who could put down the rebellion.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Between 1,000 and 1,400 slaves are believed to have been on the island at the time.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Three days before the revolt, Mustafa planned to ask Pinto to allow him to move back to Fort St.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Elmo after claiming that the air in Floriana was causing him harm.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The uprising was to commence with Pinto's assassination at around 14:00 on 29 June 1749, following a celebratory banquet at the Grand Master's Palace.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Imselleti was to kill the Grand Master using a poisoned knife, aided by Giovanni Battista and some other slaves.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The assassins then planned on throwing a vase into one of the courtyards and exposing Pinto's head.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] This was a signal for the remaining slaves to rise up, kill the other Christians within the palace and take over the Palace Armoury, where they would arm themselves.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] A simultaneous uprising was planned among the slaves working in the Forni della Signoria, who were to link up with the palace slaves and then proceed to free and arm the other Muslims in the Gran Prigione.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Elmo, while Mustafa was to lead an uprising within the fort itself to facilitate its takeover and allow him to take charge of the uprising.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Further revolts were planned in the Birgu and Senglea bagnios upon a signal from St.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Elmo; the slaves in these cities were to occupy Fort St.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] A separate uprising was planned among the slaves on board the *Capitana*, *San Luigi* and *San Nicola*, the three ships which constituted the Hospitaller naval squadron.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Before these ships departed Malta on 5 May, Mustafa had distributed arsenic to a group of galley slaves who were to find an opportune moment to poison the knights and rise up, take over the ships and sail them back to Malta to support the uprising on land.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] This was not the conspirators' first attempt to recruit him, and a quarrel ensued when Cassar refused and he was physically assaulted by Giovanni Battista.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The tavern's proprietor – Giuseppe Cohen, a recent convert from Judaism to Catholicism – overheard parts of the conversation and confronted Cassar, who told him about the plot.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Cohen persuaded Cassar to meet him at dawn the following day so that they could notify the Grand Master of the conspiracy together.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] At around 20:00, Cassar revealed what he knew of the plot to his commanding officer, the Knight Commander de Viguier, but the latter did not understand the significance of this due to a language barrier.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] De Viguier asked Cassar to meet him the following day with an interpreter, and at around 22:00 de Viguier notified Pinto of what he knew so far.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] On 7 June, Cassar did not show up to his planned meeting with Cohen, so the latter went alone to the palace and requested an audience with Pinto.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] He informed the Grand Master of what he had learnt from Cassar, corroborating de Viguier's account and providing additional details.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Since Cassar had been aware of the plot for weeks prior to 6 June, it was Cohen who received the credit for uncovering the plot rather than Cassar.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] (labelled "Z") as depicted on a 17th century map of Valletta.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The building which existed in 1749 was demolished and replaced by the building which still exists today in 1757–1760.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The trial of the conspirators was held at the Gran Corte della Castellania in Valletta.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Cassar was the first to be interrogated, followed by Giovanni Battista and Antonio de Viguier who were arrested on 8 June.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Interrogations initially began without the use of torture, but Pinto directly authorised the use of torture on Giovanni Battista in an attempt to compel him to reveal more information about the plot.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] He was subjected to the *corda* and *cavalletto* and quickly confessed and named some of the other slaves involved.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] He never named Mustafa, suggesting that he had been unaware of the latter's role in the plot.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] When the seriousness of the plot was realised, Pinto ordered that the trial be administered according to military lines; this effectively removed limitations on the use of torture, allowed for longer interrogations, and restricted the proceedings in secrecy.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Three judges – Giacomo Nataleo, Giulio Cumbo and Pietro de Franchis – were appointed, while Carlo Guicciardi and Fortunato Bencini led the prosecution and the notaries Onorato Grillet Sciberras and Pietro Antonio Buhagiar served on the tribunal.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] De Viguier was the second person to be interrogated using torture, and other individuals followed suit as more details of the plot and names of other conspirators were revealed.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Following further confessions, Mustafa was suspected of being the mastermind behind the plot by 21 June, and a week later he was placed under house arrest.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] By 5 July, around 80 slaves were implicated in the plot and had been tortured.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Prior to their execution, attempts were made to compel the slaves to convert to Christianity; Mishud agreed to be baptised while Haec Musa did not.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] One slave died during torture on 10 July; his body was subsequently buried at the Marsa mosque.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] By mid-July, several Greek Christians were also under suspicion of being involved in the plot.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] On 21 July, four slaves were tortured with pincers while being paraded through Valletta bound on carts, before they were executed outside Porta Reale.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Two who had been baptised prior to execution were strangled while those who refused baptism were stabbed to death; the bodies of all four were beheaded post mortem.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Giovanni Battista, two Muslim slaves (one of whom was baptised), and two Christian soldiers in the Grand Master's guard were executed on 23 July.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The Christians were strangled and beheaded post mortem, while the Muslim was tortured with pincers before being beheaded.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Four palace slaves were executed on 28 July; all were tortured with pincers, and two who were baptised were strangled and beheaded post mortem while two who were not were beheaded alive.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] 64 Muslim slaves were sentenced to serve on the galleys on 3 August.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Three slaves and two free Christians including Antonio de Viguier were executed on 5 August.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Two of the slaves were baptised prior to execution; one of these was strangled before being beheaded while the other was hanged.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The slave who refused baptism was tortured with pincers before being strangled and beheaded, while the two Christians were strangled.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Seven other slaves – six of whom were Muslim religious leaders known as *papassi* – were executed on 9 August by being strangled and beheaded; five of these died as Muslims and were tortured with pincers prior to being executed, while two who had been baptised were spared the additional torture.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] When the Hospitaller galley squadron returned to Malta in September, some of the galley slaves were tortured after being suspected of being involved in the plot.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] On 27 September, a slave on board the galley *San Nicola* confessed that there had been a plot to poison the crew and soldiers and then sail to Algiers.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] One of the galley slaves committed suicide in prison on 11 October, and four galley slaves were executed on 14 October while three others along with a free neophyte were executed on 16 October.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Those executed in October were all baptised, and were strangled before their bodies were beheaded.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Two days later, eight slaves were whipped and branded with the letter *R* (for *ribelli*) beneath their right eyes, and were condemned to be rowers for life.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] On 1 November, another Ottoman slave who had been implicated in the plot died after falling ill following torture.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Investigations and torture continued after poison was discovered hidden in the kitchen of the Grand Master's Palace in June 1750, but no further executions are known to have taken place.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] In total, the trial involved 151 suspects.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The 35 people who were executed included 29 Muslim slaves (17 of whom converted to Christianity prior to execution) and 6 free Christians (3 of whom had previously participated in the *Lupa* revolt).
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Two others died during or after being tortured, one committed suicide, and 72 others were condemned to the galleys (including 8 who were branded).
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The severed limbs of those quartered and the heads of those beheaded were displayed publicly at Fort St.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Angelo and Fort Ricasoli after the executions.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The headless bodies of those beheaded were burnt, with those who had died as Muslims being burnt separately from those who were Christians (including the newly-baptised).
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The burnt remains of the latter subsequently received a Cristian burial.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Property owned by those executed was auctioned off in September 1749.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The plot prompted an increase in anti-Muslim and anti-Turkish sentiment within the Maltese population, and several violent incidents are known to have occurred in the days after the plot was foiled.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] On 19 June 1749, before Mustafa was placed under house arrest, a group of Valletta residents threatened to stone him while he was going around the city with attendants and a carriage.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The next day, villagers from Birkirkara, Qormi and Naxxar armed themselves and attempted to march to Mustafa's residence in Floriana but were held back by the Hospitaller authorities.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] On 22 June, a mob of some 8,000–10,000 Maltese gathered outside the Floriana residence and once again threatened to stone or lynch Mustafa.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Pinto sent reinforcements to guard the Pasha, who was moved to more secure quarters at Fort St.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] On 25 June, another mob mainly composed of youths attacked and ransacked the mosque in Marsa; the Hospitallers had to send soldiers to restore order and to prevent them from burning it down.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] On 29 June, the day of the planned revolt, the Hospitallers raised a red Ottoman flag on Fort St.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Elmo in order to deceive any Muslim ships which might attempt to provide naval assistance to the would-be rebels.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Cannons along the fortifications were loaded as a precaution, and 400 men commanded by the Grand Falconer held a parade throughout the streets of Valletta.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Between June 1749 and January 1750, laws governing the movement of slaves were made stricter.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] They could not go outside city limits, and were not to approach any fortifications.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] They were not allowed to gather anywhere except their mosque, and were to sleep only in bagnios.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] They could not carry any weapons or keys to government buildings.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The thwarting of the plot was commemorated by several thanksgiving celebrations in the churches of Valletta and Birgu in August and September 1749.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] On 6 June 1750 – the first anniversary of the plot's discovery – public processions were held throughout Malta.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] That date continued to be celebrated as a day of thanksgiving in subsequent decades.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] In recognition for his role in uncovering the conspiracy, Cohen was given an annual pension of around 750 scudi and he was granted the right of enjoyment of a property in Valletta's *Strada San Giacomo* (now Merchants Street).
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The property which was granted to Cohen had previously been the seat of Valletta's *Università* until it moved to new premises in 1721.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Cohen and his descendants were granted right of use on 14 August 1749, and the property remained in his family's hands until 1773, when the building was taken over to house the Monte di Pietà and the family was given an annuity as compensation.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The building still exists and it continues to house the Monte di Pietà.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Mustafa also sent a letter to Ottoman grand vizier Seyyid Abdullah Pasha defending his position.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] These negotiations fell through, and Mustafa finally left Malta on board a French ship bound for Constantinople on 13 March 1751.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Mustafa's later life after returning to the Ottoman Empire is unclear, with sources making several contradictory claims regarding his subsequent fate.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The plot is described in a wide variety of published and unpublished primary sources, making it one of the best-documented events in the history of Hospitaller Malta.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Following the first round of trials, the Hospitallers prepared an official report which was circulated to European courts at the end of July 1749.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] An updated version of the report which includes an addendum describing the second round of trials in September was presented to the Order's Council on 4 November 1749, and a copy of this has been preserved at the Archives of the Order of Malta which are held at the National Library of Malta.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The Hospitallers are believed to have encouraged the dissemination of the official report, which was published in numerous pamphlets and periodicals and was translated into multiple languages including Spanish, Portuguese, French, English and German.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The attempted revolt and its aftermath was reported in contemporary newspapers throughout Europe and in European colonies in the Americas, with varying degrees of accuracy.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Unofficial descriptions of the plot also circulated, but the Order discouraged or attempted to suppress such publications.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Examples of these include accounts in Italian by Giuseppe Novi and by Piccolomini, Grand Prior of Barletta, an account in French by the Knight Commander de Viguier, and several accounts in Portuguese.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Although credited to Michele Acciard, it is widely believed that Gozitan author Giovanni Pietro Francesco Agius de Soldanis had a hand in writing at least some parts of the account.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The book caused considerable controversy since it attacked the Order and argued for the rights of the Maltese.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] This caused it to be banned in Malta, and de Soldanis was briefly exiled to Rome and had to defend himself in front of the Pope before he was allowed to return to Malta in 1752.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Unpublished sources include several eyewitness accounts by Maltese individuals, by Hospitaller knights or by foreigners who were residing on Malta at the time of the plot.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] This source has been studied and published by historian William Zammit, who wrote a book about the plot in 2023.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The most significant visual record of the conspiracy is a set of 19 drawings which depict the *Lupa* revolt, the plot, and its aftermath including the torture and executions.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The drawings are an example of naïve art by an unknown artist, and they are believed to have been produced sometime after 1758, possibly by an eyewitness to the executions.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Numbering on the drawings indicates that they originally formed part of a set of at least 24, but remainder are lost.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The drawings generally corroborate the sequence of events noted in written sources, although they contain some inaccuracies.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The surviving drawings are held by Heritage Malta and they were exhibited to the public at the Inquisitor's Palace in 2024–2025.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] A more fanciful rendition of the executions was depicted in a German engraving produced in 1750.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] French artist Antoine de Favray produced a painting dated 1749 depicting a meeting between a group of slaves formulating the plot; this is now held at the Mdina Cathedral Museum.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Favray also produced an anatomical drawing of the severed head of one of the executed slaves, Stefano Lorenzo Maria alias Ibrahim.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] A 1750 ex-voto painting commemorating the conversion of Carmine Giuseppe Xaverio alias Imhammet, one of the galley slaves executed in September 1749, is held at a sanctuary in Trapani, Sicily.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The poem "*Fuchech Nithaddet Malta*" (modern Maltese: "Fuqek Nitħaddet Malta", English: "I Talk About You, Malta"), an early example of Maltese literature, was written some time after the attempted revolt.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Its author is unknown, but it is sometimes attributed to Giacomo Marchese as it was preserved among his papers.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] The plot of 1749 is the only known major attempt at slave rebellion on land in early modern Christian Europe, and it has also been described by some sources as an attempted coup d'état.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Whether or not the plot could have succeeded had it not been foiled is a matter of debate.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Historian William Zammit wrote in 2023 that while the assassination of Pinto and the revolt within the Grand Master's Palace "could have been carried out with relative ease", the rest of the plot including the capture of Fort St.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Angelo and the takeover of the rest of Malta would have been difficult to implement, even with assistance from North Africa and the Ottoman Empire.
[src:malta/1749-muslim-slave-revolt-plot-in-malta] Had the plot succeeded, it is likely that he would have been disposed of by Mustafa.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] A referendum on European Union membership was held in Malta on 8 March 2003.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] The subsequent April 2003 general elections were won by the Nationalist Party, which was in favour of EU membership, the opposition Labour Party having opposed joining.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] The referendum saw the highest turnout in an EU membership referendum (91%) and the lowest support for joining of any of the nine countries that held referendums on joining the EU in 2003.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] Malta's first relations with the European Economic Community (EEC) saw the signing of an Association Agreement in December 1970.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] This agreement called for the creation of a customs union based on free trade between Malta and the Bloc.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] Malta submitted a formal application to join the European Community in July 1990, which was met with a positive opinion from the European Commission.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] However the application was suspended in 1996 with a new Labour government.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] After the Nationalist Party won the 1998 election, the new government reactivated Malta's membership application.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] Negotiations to join were finished at the Copenhagen summit in December 2002 and Malta was invited to join the EU in 2004.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] The government of Malta announced in January 2003 that a non-binding referendum on membership would be held on 8 March 2003 at the same time as local elections.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] In the run up to the referendum polls showed voters were evenly divided over EU membership.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] The Nationalist government argued that Malta would receive EU funds for the roads and tourist industry.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] They said that Malta needed the EU in order to cope with globalisation and accused the opposition of scaremongering.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] The Labour opposition feared that EU membership would cost jobs due to the lowering of trade barriers and jeopardise Malta's independence.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] They preferred that Malta should form a partnership with the EU rather than seeking membership and called on Maltese votes to either spoil their ballot papers, abstain or vote no.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] One billboard for the no campaign showed the Prime Minister Eddie Fenech Adami wearing a Diaper made of the flag of Europe.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] The largest trade union in Malta, the General Workers' Union opposed membership.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] The question voted in on in the referendum was confirmed on 3 January 2003.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] Supporters of the Nationalist party celebrated the result of the referendum but the Labour leader Alfred Sant did not concede defeat and said the issue would be settled at the upcoming general election.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] He argued that only 48% of registered voters had voted yes and that therefore a majority had opposed membership by voting no, abstaining or spoiling their ballot.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] The day after the referendum the Prime Minister called the election for 12 April as expected, though it was not required until January 2004.
[src:malta/2003-maltese-european-union-membership-referendum] The main issue in the 2003 election was EU membership and the Nationalist party's victory enabled Malta to join on 1 May 2004.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] A referendum on divorce was held in Malta on 28 May 2011.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] Voters were asked whether they approved of a new law to introduce allowing divorces, as at that time, Malta was one of only three countries in the world (along with the Philippines and the Vatican City) in which divorce was not permitted.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] The proposal was approved by 53% of voters, resulting in a law allowing divorce under certain conditions being enacted later in the year.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] A private member's bill was tabled in the House of Representatives by Jeffrey Pullicino Orlando, then a Nationalist Member of Parliament and Evarist Bartolo, then a Labour Member of Parliament.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] The text of the bill, which had been changed twice, did not provide for the holding of a referendum.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] This was eventually provided for through a separate Parliamentary resolution under the Referenda Act authorising a facultative, non-binding referendum to be held.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] The Catholic Church in Malta encouraged a "no" vote through a pastoral letter issued on the Sunday before the referendum day.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] Complaints were made that religious pressure was being brought to bear upon voters.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] Around 8 per cent of marriages in Malta are already annulled by the Catholic Church.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] Ballot papers had both English and Maltese questions printed on them.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] The question, which resembled the proposal approved by Irish voters in the Irish divorce referendum of 1995, was somewhat controversial.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] It was claimed that it did not reflect the content of the private member's bill.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] Although for the purposes of the referendum the whole country was regarded to be a single constituency — taking into account electoral districts — in only three out of the thirteen did the "no" vote reach a majority.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] Discussion on the divorce bill started in earnest soon after the result was announced.
[src:malta/2011-maltese-divorce-referendum] In the second and third readings a number of MPs still voted against the bill.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was most recently revised for its ninth edition of 1940.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] Abridged versions and a supplement exist.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was initially the basis for the 2021 *Cambridge Greek Lexicon*, although subsequently that became a complete rewrite from scratch.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The lexicon was begun in the 19th century, and is now in its ninth (revised) edition, published in 1940.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was based on the earlier *Handwörterbuch der griechischen Sprache* by the German lexicographer Franz Passow (first published in 1819, fourth edition 1831), which in turn was based on Johann Gottlob Schneider's *Kritisches griechisch-deutsches Handwörterbuch*.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Lexicon* has served as the basis for all later lexicographical work on the ancient Greek language, such as the ongoing Greek–Spanish dictionary project *Diccionario Griego–Español* (DGE).
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is now conventionally referred to as *Liddell & Scott*, *Liddell–Scott–Jones*, or *LSJ*, and its three sizes are sometimes referred to as "The Little Liddell", "The Middle Liddell" and "The Big Liddell" or "The Great Scott".
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ main edition has 116,502 entries.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] According to Stuart Jones's preface to the ninth (1925) edition, the creation of the *Lexicon* was originally proposed by David Alphonso Talboys, an Oxford publisher.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was published by the Clarendon Press at Oxford rather than by Talboys, who died before the first edition (1843) was complete.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The first editor of the LSJ, Henry George Liddell, was Dean of Christ Church, Oxford, and the father of Alice Liddell, the eponymous Alice of the writings of Lewis Carroll.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The eighth edition (1897) was the last edition published during Liddell's lifetime.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ is sometimes compared and contrasted with *A Latin Dictionary* by Lewis and Short, which was also published by Oxford University Press (OUP).
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is also sometimes compared with the Bauer lexicon, which is a similar work focused on the Greek of the New Testament.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ's definitions reflect the Victorian morality of its time, using euphemism.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, χέζω (*chezo*, 'to shit'), is translated as "ease oneself, do one's need"; βινέω (*bineo*, 'to fuck') as "inire, coire, of illicit intercourse"; and λαικάζω (*laikazo*, 'to suck cocks') as "to wench".
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] Two condensed editions of LSJ were published by Oxford University Press and remain in print.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1843, the same year as the full lexicon's publication, *A Lexicon: Abridged from Liddell and Scott's Greek–English Lexicon*, sometimes called "the Little Liddell" was published.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, a reprint, re-typeset in 2007, of the 1909 edition is available from Simon Wallenberg Press.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1889, an intermediate edition of the lexicon, *An Intermediate Greek–English Lexicon*, was prepared on the basis of the seventh edition (1883) of LSJ.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] After the publication of the ninth edition in 1940, and shortly after the deaths of both Stuart Jones and McKenzie, the OUP maintained a list of *addenda et corrigenda* ("additions and corrections"), which was bound with subsequent printings.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] However, in 1968, these were replaced by a Supplement to the LSJ.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] Neither the *addenda* nor the Supplement has ever been merged into the main text, which still stands as originally composed by Liddell, Scott, Jones, and McKenzie.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement was initially edited by M.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] Glare, editor of the *Oxford Latin Dictionary* (not to be confused with Lewis and Short's *A Latin Dictionary*).
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] Since 1988, it has been edited by Glare and Anne A.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] As the title page of the *Lexicon* makes clear (and the prefaces to the main text and to the Supplement attest), this editorial work has been performed "with the cooperation of many scholars".
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement primarily takes the form of a list of additions and corrections to the main text, sorted by entry.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The supplemental entries are marked with signs to show the nature of the changes they call for.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] Thus, a user of the *Lexicon* can consult the Supplement after consulting the main text to see whether scholarship after Jones and McKenzie has provided any new information about a particular word.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] As of 2005, the most recent revision of the Supplement, published in 1996, contains 320 pages of corrections to the main text, as well as other materials.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The small "x" indicates that this word did not appear in the main text at all; "S.*fr*." refers to the collected fragmentary works of Sophocles.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] One interesting new source of lexicographic material in the revised Supplement is the Mycenean inscriptions.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The ninth edition of LSJ has been freely available in electronic form since 2007, having been digitized by the Perseus Project.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] Diogenes, a free software package, incorporates the Perseus data and allows easy offline consultation of LSJ on Mac OS X, Windows, and Linux platforms.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] Marcion is another open source application that includes the Perseus LSJ.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] For mobile devices, both the Kindle E-Ink and the iPhone/iPod Touch feature data ported from Perseus.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Android market also currently offers the intermediate LSJ as an offline downloadable app for free or for a small price.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] A CD-ROM version published and sold by Logos Bible Software also incorporates the Supplement's additions to the ninth edition of LSJ.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] A new online version of LSJ was released in 2011 by the Thesaurus Linguae Graecae (TLG).
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The TLG version corrects "a large number of typographical errors", and includes links to the extensive TLG textual corpus.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] A Kindle version, the "Complete Liddell & Scott's Lexicon with Inflections", is also available: it allows searches of most Classical Greek word-forms and supports a growing number of Ancient/Classical Greek texts for the device.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Lexicon has been translated into Modern Greek by Xenophon Moschos, ed.: Michael Konstantinidis and was published by Anestis Konstantinidis in 1904 with the title *H.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] Scott – Α.* Κωνσταντινίδου (Μέγα Λεξικόν τῆς Ἑλληνικῆς Γλώσσης).
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] Also, a supplement compiled by a group of Greek philologists.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] An Italian translation of the *Intermediate Liddell-Scott*, entitled *Dizionario illustrato Greco-Italiano* was published in 1975 by Le Monnier, edited by Q.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] LSJ was the basis of the project of John Chadwick and James Diggle at Cambridge to publish the *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* of 2021.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] Although it was initially conceived as a mere update of LSJ, the editors eventually decided to start afresh since they considered LSJ "too antiquated in concept, design and content".
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The CGL has a smaller scope than the LSJ (and also the *Brill Dictionary of Ancient Greek*), and is unlikely to replace it; however, it is still more comprehensive than the Middle Liddell, which it intends to replace.
[src:malta/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* uses contemporary language for its definitions and, unlike the LSJ, no longer elides the meaning of words considered offensive in Victorian times.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] The work is usually referred to as *Lewis and Short* after the names of its editors, Charlton T.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] It was derived from the 1850 English translation by Ethan Allen Andrews of an earlier Latin–German dictionary, *Wörterbuch der Lateinischen Sprache*, by the German philologist Wilhelm Freund, in turn based on I.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Scheller’s Latin–German dictionary of 1783.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] The Andrews translation was partially revised by Freund himself, then by Henry Drisler, and was finally edited by Short and Lewis.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] The division of labour between the two editors was remarkably unequal.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] In 1890 Lewis published a heavily abridged version of the dictionary, entitled *An Elementary Latin Dictionary*, for the use of students.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Sometimes called the *Elementary Lewis*, it is still in print today.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] The adoption of the book by Oxford University Press was the result of the failure of its own project to create a new Latin–English dictionary in 1875.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Henry Nettleship and John Mayor had been commissioned to produce a new Latin dictionary based on a fresh reading of the sources, but after Mayor withdrew from the project, Nettleship was unable to complete it on his own; he eventually published his research as notes on Lewis and Short.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] While the Press had earlier published John Riddle's 1835 translation of Scheller's Latin–German dictionary, this was a much more expensive book.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] The Press thus adopted *Harpers' Latin Dictionary* as a stopgap measure, paying Harper and Brothers 10 per cent royalties.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Harper and Brothers sold its rights to the American Book Company in 1899, shortly before its bankruptcy.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] From the time of its publication, many scholars have criticized the dictionary for its errors and inconsistencies.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Because of various circumstances, however, no replacement was attempted until 1933, with the *Oxford Latin Dictionary*, which was completed in 1983.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] However, the *Oxford Latin Dictionary* stops at 200CE.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] The dictionary's full text (year 1879) is available online at numerous websites.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Among classicists "never a very good dictionary", Lewis and Short has been largely superseded by the *Oxford Latin Dictionary*, called the *OLD* for short.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Lewis and Short incorporated material from existing Latin dictionaries; the *OLD*, by contrast, started from scratch, following procedures similar to those of the well-regarded *Oxford English Dictionary*.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Thanks to the increased availability of modern editions, the *OLD* editors had access to a larger variety of classical works.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] It was decided in the *OLD'*s planning that the *OLD* would not encompass Latin written later than AD 200, with a few exceptions.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Although classicists still consult Lewis and Short, they tend to prefer the *OLD*.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Lewis and Short retains value for its refined sense of the nuances of English diction as it interfaces with Latin diction (in contrast with *OLD*'s preference for plainer diction) and also for the sensitivity of its quotations from classical texts, reflecting this.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Lewis and Short's primary focus is on classical Latin, not medieval Latin.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Nevertheless, Lewis and Short is consulted by medievalists, renaissance specialists, and early modernists, as it includes some late and medieval Latin, if somewhat inconsistently, and classical Latin usages are very relevant in medieval Latin.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] The *Dictionary of Medieval Latin from British Sources* supplements Lewis and Short for medieval Latin vocabulary.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Another dictionary focused on medieval Latin is J.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] Niermeyer's **Mediae Latinitatis Lexicon Minus**, first published in 1976, with an enhanced second edition in year 2002, about 1500 pages.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] On occasion people confuse Lewis and Short (or L&S) with Liddell and Scott, its Greek counterpart, entitled *A Greek–English Lexicon*.
[src:malta/a-latin-dictionary] The 1925 and later editions of Liddell and Scott are commonly referred to by the abbreviation *LSJ* after the names of its editors Liddell, Scott and the editor of the 1925 revision, Henry Stuart Jones.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The **Abbey of Santa Giustina** is a 10th-century Benedictine abbey complex located in front of the Prato della Valle in central Padua, region of Veneto, Italy.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Adjacent to the former monastery is the basilica church of Santa Giustina, initially built in the 6th century, but whose present form derives from a 17th-century reconstruction.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] A church dedicated to Saint Justina of Padua and other 4th-century Christian martyrs of Padua, was present at the site by the 520s, erected under the patronage of the Prefect Opilius and housing the relics of the saint.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The church was already described as lavish in decoration in the 565 biography "Life of St Martin", written by Venantius Fortunatus.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] By the 10th century, monks ministered to pilgrims who came to the basilica to venerate the saints' relics.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] In 971, the Bishop of Padua placed the community under the Rule of St.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Renovations were soon begun on the basilica.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] On 2 August 1052, workers putatively exhumed remains of various saints, including Maximus the Confessor, Felicitas of Padua, Julian the Hospitaller, and even some identified as the Holy Innocents.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] In 1110 the abbey was sacked by the troops of the future Holy Roman Emperor Henry V during his invasion of Lombardy, in order to punish the monks for their loyalty to Pope Pascal II.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] In 1117, the complex was devastated by the powerful Verona earthquake.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] After the basilica and monastery were rebuilt, excavations resumed and in 1174 the remains of the patroness of the abbey were discovered, and in 1177, some remains attributed to St Luke the Evangelist.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] A period of decline in the observance of its way of life began to develop in the monastic community.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] At the same time, the monks were led by a number of very spiritual abbots, such as Arnaldo of Limena, who died while imprisoned by Ezzelino III da Romano and is honored as "Blessed", as is Nicholas of Prussia.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] By the 1370s the community had declined to three monks.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The abbey, however, reached the height of its influence under the leadership of Ludovico Barbo, who, despite being a canon regular and not a monk, was appointed as abbot by the bishop in order to undertake a reform of the monastic life in the abbey.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] He was successful and the abbey became the nucleus of the Congregation of Santa Giustina, which spread to include monasteries throughout Europe who came under the guidance of the Abbot of Santa Giustina.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The abbey developed ties with centers of learning across the continent.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] In 1504 the Abbey of Monte Cassino was made subject to Santa Giustina in Padua, and together they became known as the Cassinese Congregation.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The religious community was suppressed in 1797 when, after the occupation of the region by Napoleon's French Revolutionary Army.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Its artworks and the most valuable collections of the abbatial library were sent to Paris by the occupying forces.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The monks were expelled and the buildings and property were sold off in 1810.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The cloisters were then used as a military hospital, later as a barracks.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The buildings were returned to the Catholic Church in 1917 and Pope Benedict XV re-established the abbey with all its ancient rights and privileges.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] He placed it under the Abbey of Praglia in nearby Teolo, which sent monks to resume monastic life there.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] On 1 November 1942 the community was declared an autonomous priory, which was established under its own abbot on 22 January 1943.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The basilica and abbey now have the government status of a national monument and operate under the authority of the Superintendent of Monuments and Civil Heritage.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The church has a layout of a Latin cross with the main axis from east to west.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] At 118.5 metres (389 ft) long and 82 metres (269 ft) wide, the Basilica of Santa Giustina is the seventh largest in Italy.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The facade is enhanced by expanse of the Prato della Valle, which it overlooks.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The presbytery with the choir, and the two chapels for saints Luke and Matthew that form the transepts.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Each has a semicircular apse and are flanked by two chapels.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Each aisle has six smaller chapels, square plan.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The 26 pillars supporting the roof domes, each dome is set directly on the barrel vaults.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The central bays are covered by eight domes covered with lead: the central one, with the lantern, is almost 70 metres (230 ft) high and is topped by a statue of copper depicting Santa Giustina, about 5 metres (16 ft) high.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The floor of the basilica was laid between 1608 and 1615 on geometric design, with yellow, white and red marble.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] There are many pieces of Greek marble, from the Basilica Opilionea.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The first chapel is dedicated to Saint James the Less.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The altar is in polychrome stones in the style of the Corbarelli family of the seventeenth century.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The white marble altarpiece shows an oil on canvas by Carlo Caliari: *Martyrdom of Saint James*.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The second chapel is dedicated to Pope Gregory I.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The 19th-century altar is mainly built with African green marble and Carrara white marble, framing a polychrome stone marquetry; The stonework was performed by the Corbarelli family.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The altarpiece is an 18th-century oil on canvas depicting *Pope Gregory I invokes the aid of the Virgin to end the plague in Rome* by Sebastiano Ricci.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Ricci's work replaced an initial painting by Carlo Cignani.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The third chapel is dedicated to Daniel of Padua.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The altar is characterized by the use of red marble from France and the marbles of Carrara and Padua; the altarpiece depicts the *Martyrdom of St Daniel* (1677) by Antonio Zanchi.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The altar is the work of the brothers Corbarelli.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The oil on canvas altarpiece depicts the *Martyrdom of Saint Placidus and companions* (1676) by Luca Giordano.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Note the refined decoration of the Corbarelli family inlaid with polychrome stone behind the altar.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The fifth chapel is dedicated to Saint Maurus.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The altarpiece is in black and white marble from Genoa; The altar of green marble, marble of Genoa, and red marble of France.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The altarpiece representing "Saint Maurus invoked by the sick" (1673) by Valentin Le Febvre.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The sixth chapel is dedicated to Saint Julien.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The altar contains the tomb of Saint Julien with his statue (1680) sculpted by Giovanni Comin.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The statues of Saints Andrew and Matthew were sculpted by Bernardo Falcone.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The seventh and last chapel on the left side of the nave is dedicated to Saint Felicity.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The chapel houses the monumental altar surmounted by the urn containing the remains of the saint, discovered in 1502 in the Chapel of Saint Prosdocime of Padua.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The sculptures are by Orazio Marinali and plays on the colors of white and red marble from France.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The statue of the saint in prayer is placed on the urn, on the sides two angels and Saints Mark and Simon.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The altar is very refined, decorated by brothers Corbarelli: it represents fountains, gardens and the unfinished façade of the basilica.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The large chapel was reorganized for the liturgical adaptations implemented in the years of the Second Vatican Council.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] In the center, a 1313 monument that houses the relics of St.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Luke the Evangelist, commissioned by the Abbot Gualpertino Mussato and originally erected in the Gothic chapel in 1562.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The monument is made of serpentine and marble of Verona.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] It is enriched with eight alabaster panels carved in bas-relief depicting angels and symbols related to the saint.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The whole rests on two granite columns, two alabaster spiral columns and the center is placed on a support in Greek marble, representing caryatid angels, supporting the whole.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The 16th-century altar, today displaced, served as a base for the monument.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] A modern wooden choir surrounds the altar.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] At the top is placed the sixteenth-century version – attributed to Alessandro Bonvicino – of the Virgin Salus Populi Patavini Constantinople.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] It is framed and supported by the bronze angels of Hamlet Sartori (1960–1961).
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The Byzantine icon of origin, according to tradition, painted by Saint Luke and brought to Padua to save from the iconoclastic fury of Constantinople, is now in a sanctuary in the monastery.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The chapel is dedicated to Blessed Arnaud Cataneo (Arnaldo da Limena).
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The altar was erected in 1681: Bernardo Falcone sculpted the angels and the statue placed above the urn that houses the relics of Blessed Arnaud.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The lateral statues of Saints Peter and St Paul are works of Orazio Marinali and Michele Fabris.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The work of marquetry of polychrome stones of the altar is the work of the Corbarelli family.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] On the large wall on the right, there is a large canvas by Antonio Balestra (1718) depicting the martyrdom of Saints Cosmas and Damian.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Opposite, on the left wall, *The Great Massacre of the Innocents* by Sebastiano Galvano, signed by the mid-sixteenth century.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Initially this work was in the church of San Benedetto Novello.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The chapel is dedicated to the Blessed Sacrament.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Before hosting the Blessed Sacrament, the chapel contained the relics of the Innocent Saints.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The ceiling is decorated with frescoes depicting angels and apostles worshiping the Blessed Sacrament.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The work is by Sebastiano Ricci made around 1700; It is characterized by the use of the trompe l'oeil.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The vault above the altar is occupied by the representation of the Eternal Father, preceded by the Apostles, represented as if placed above the walls of the chapel, and attracted by the Eucharist carried in triumph by An angelic crowd.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The altar is a work made in several times in the forties of the seventeenth century.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The design is by Lorenzo Bedogni by Pietro Paolo Corbarelli and their sons Simone, Antonio and Francesco around 1656.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] It was completed in 1674 by Giuseppe Sardi and Josse the Court who fashioned the two angels worshipers while the bronze statues on the Tabernacle were cast Carlo Trabucco (1697).
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The other sculptures are by Michele and Alessandro Fabris Tremignon.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] It is elevated in relation to the rest of the building and is accessible by a monumental staircase.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Below is a large crypt, now a winter chapel.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The balustrades are the work of Francesco Contini (1630).
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] On the sides, at the top, niches inside, two busts that ideally represent the two Roman patricians Vitaliano (right) and Opilione (left) works of Giovanni Francesco de Surdis of 1561.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Decorated with "Florentine" combining fine inlays of marble on which are placed pieces of mother-of-pearl, coral, lapis lazuli, carnelian, pearls and other precious materials.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The delicate work was carried out between 1637 and 1643 by Pietro Paolo Corbarelli designed by Giovan Battista Nigetti, brother of the famous Matteo Nigetti.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] On 7 October 1627, with great pomp, the body of Saint Justine was placed under the altar.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The painting of the altarpiece The martyrdom of Saint Justine by Paolo Veronese oil on canvas from 1576.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The chapel is the work of Genoese artist Filippo Parodi in 1689.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The artist took charge of the architectural, decorative and sculptural design including the ceiling, adorned by an angelic stucco crowd.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] In the center is the Pietà, surrounded by two statues of Mary Magdalene and John the Apostle.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The altar houses the tomb containing the remains of the second bishop of Padua, Saint Maximus.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The statue group: saint maxime, the angels who hold the insignia of the bishop and saint James is the work of Michele Fabris (1681), while the statue of St.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Bartholomew is the result of the scissors of Bernardo Falcone (1682).
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The altar in marquetry of polychrome stone, is the work of the Corbarelli family.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The great space is dominated by two imposing canvases: on the right The mission of the Apostles (1631) of Battista Bissoni and Saints Cosmas and Damian saved by the angel (1718) of Antonio Balestra, this one comes from the Church of the Mercy.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Below the paintings are the confessionals and a pulpit from the seventeenth century.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] At the bottom of the chapel is a monument in Greek and African marble where the body of Saint Matthias the Apostle rests.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The work is inspired by the reliquary tomb of Saint-Luc which is anterior.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] It was completed in 1562 by Giovanni Francesco de Surdis who carved the bas-reliefs representing the apostles.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Behind the ark opens the door leading to the Martyrs' room.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The 15th century vault is decorated in the style of the Renaissance.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The bas-reliefs are attributed to the circle of Bartolomeo Bellano.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] A small alabaster temple with rich ironwork houses a representation of the virgin.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] It is accessible from the right transept.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Built in 1564 on the ruins of the ancient abbey church of the Middle Ages, it was designed to allow passage to the Sanctuary of St.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The corridor, painted in the 16th and 17th centuries, is counter-vaulted and, in the middle, an octagonal space covered by a dome decorated with fresco by Giacomo Ceruti.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] In the center there is the Well of the Martyrs: built on the orders of the abbot Angelo Sangrino in 1565 above the medieval well (still visible in the basement) which was in the middle of the nave of the original basilica.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The octagonal marble of Verona marble and alabaster, is finely worked.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] A grid allows to see at the bottom the bones of the martyrs of the Diocletian era discovered here in 1269 by Blessed Giacoma.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] In the west corner a piece of the mosaic decoration that adorned the floor of the opilionea basilica of the sixth century is still visible.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] At the bottom an altar of the sixteenth century on a painting by Pietro Damini The discovery of the Well of the Martyrs and the miraculous power of the twelve candle count among the best works of the artist.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Also visible is a large iron cage, dating back to the Middle Ages, which contained the remains of Saint Luke.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The two statues of saints Peter and Paul are the work of Francesco Segala.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Following the corridor of the Martyrs is the sanctuary of Prosdocimus of Padua or Sanctuary of Santa Maria.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] One of the oldest buildings in Veneto: dated from the 6th century.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] It is the only preserved vestige of the opilionea basilica.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Originally it was a chapel dedicated to the preservation of relics.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The space is conceived on the plane of the Greek cross and is characterized by a very elegant awning composed of dome all painted in grotesque in the sixteenth century to replace the original mosaic decoration.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] It was the burial place of the first bishops of Padua, including the first, St Prosdocime of Padua, whose body rests in the altar of 1564.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] It consists of a Roman sarcophagus placed on the right (in relation to the " apse).
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Above the altar is a bas-relief depicting St Prosdocime of Padua in the Roman aristocrat's dating from the 5th century.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] In front of the apse a pergola, in Greek marble, astonishing work of the sixth century practically intact preserved in the initial position of Iconostase Along the wall of the small entrance hall, remains of frescoes from the twelfth century, decorations from the 16th century.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The tympanum of the door of the basilica opilionea of the sixth century.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The arch placed on top of the altar (1682) contains the remains of Urio who was the guardian priest of the church of Santi Apostoli in Constantinople who saved the relics of St.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] Matthew, Icon of the Virgin of the iconoclastic fury bearing the whole until Patavium.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The statue of Sant'Urio, the angels and the saints Thomas and Thaddeus are by Bernardo Falcone.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The work of marquetry in polychromatic stones is by Corbarelli.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The chapel built during the first half of the 17th century was originally used for the Blessed Sacrament, which was transferred to one of the apsidal chapels.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The present aspect dates from 1675 with the sanctuary for the relics of Saints Innocents (the remains of three victims of Herod).
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] "The disarray of Santa Rachel" is by Giovanni Comin (1690); The two saints: James the Minor and John are attributed to Michele Fabris.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The work of marquetry in polychrome stone is by Corbarelli.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The altar is erected in black and white marble of Genoa.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The table of the altarpiece: Saint Benedict welcomes Saint Placid and Saint Maurus by Palma the Younger.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The columns that support the altar are of Salò marble.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The painting of the altarpiece depicts 'The Death of Saint Scholastica' is by Luca Giordano in 1674.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The painting of the altarpiece dated 1674 by Johann Carl Loth shows the "Martyrdom of St.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The painting of the altarpiece *Ecstasy of St.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] The table of the altarpiece is attributed to Paolo Veronese in collaboration with his students, he represents *The Conversion of St.
[src:malta/abbey-of-santa-giustina] On the left wall a canvas in a lunette represents the same subject, this work is by Gaspare Diziani formerly in the *Chiesa delle Terese*.
[src:malta/malta-p01] With a population of about 574,250 spread over an area of 316 km2 (122 sq mi), Malta is the world's tenth-smallest country by area and the ninth-most densely populated.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Various sources consider the country to consist of a single urban region, for which reason it is often described as a city-state.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta has been inhabited since at least 6500 BC, during the Mesolithic.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Its location in the centre of the Mediterranean has historically given it great geostrategic importance, with a succession of powers having ruled the islands and shaped its culture and society.
[src:malta/malta-p01] These include the Phoenicians, Carthaginians, Greeks, and Romans in antiquity; the Arabs, Normans, and Aragonese during the Middle Ages; and the Knights Hospitaller, French, and British in the modern era.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta came under British rule in the early 19th century and served as the headquarters for the British Mediterranean Fleet.
[src:malta/malta-p01] It was besieged by the Axis powers during World War II and was an important Allied base for North Africa and the Mediterranean.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta achieved independence in 1964, and established its current parliamentary republic in 1974.
[src:malta/malta-p01] It has been a member state of the Commonwealth of Nations and the United Nations since independence; it joined the European Union in 2004 and the eurozone monetary union in 2008.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta's long history of foreign rule and its proximity to both Europe and North Africa have influenced its art, music, cuisine, and architecture.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta has close historical and cultural ties to Italy and especially Sicily; and while Maltese and English are its official languages, between 62 and 66 percent of Maltese people speak or have significant knowledge of the Italian language, which had official status from 1530 to 1934.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta was an early centre of Christianity, and Catholicism is the state religion, although the country's constitution guarantees freedom of conscience and religious worship.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta is a developed country with an advanced, high-income economy.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The English name *Malta* derives from Italian and Maltese *Malta*, from medieval Arabic *Māliṭā* (مَالِطَا), from classical Latin *Melita*, from Latinised or Doric forms of the ancient Greek *Melítē* (Μελίτη), of uncertain origin.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The name *Melítē*—shared by the Croatian island Mljet in antiquity—literally means "place of honey" or "sweetness", derived from the combining form of *méli* (μέλι, "honey" or any similarly sweet thing) and the suffix *-ē* (-η).
[src:malta/malta-p01] The ancient Greeks may have given the island this name after Malta's endemic subspecies of bees.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The name was then applied to all of Malta by the Greeks and to its ancient capital at Mdina by the Romans.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta has been inhabited from at least c.
[src:malta/malta-p01] 6500 BC, with the arrival of Mesolithic hunter-gatherers likely originating from Sicily.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Discoveries at Latnija Cave led by the Maltese archaeologist Eleanor Scerri included the remains of hearths, stone tools and an abundant and diverse range of animal bones.
[src:malta/malta-p01] These included indigenous red deer that are now extinct, fish and marine mammals, as well as abundant edible marine gastropods.
[src:malta/malta-p01] To arrive on Malta, these hunter-gatherers had to cross around 100 kilometres (62 mi) of open water, documenting the longest yet-known sea crossing by hunter-gatherers in the Mediterranean.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The extinction of the dwarf hippos, giant swans and dwarf elephants has historically been linked to the earliest arrival of humans on Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p01] However this seems unlikely since recent work suggests these animals went extinct many thousands of years before the arrival of the first people, and no such animals were found in association with the earliest known Mesolithic hunter-gatherers.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The claim for an earlier occupation of the island by Neanderthals is widely rejected.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Supplementary Information Neolithic Farmers, also originating from Sicily, are thought to have arrived on the islands by around 5400 BC.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Prehistoric farming settlements dating to the Early Neolithic include the Għar Dalam cave site in the uppermost layers associated with domesticated animals.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The Neolithic population on Malta grew cereals, raised livestock and, in common with other ancient Mediterranean cultures, worshipped a fertility figure.
[src:malta/malta-p01] A culture of megalithic temple builders then either supplanted or arose from this early period.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Around 3500 BC, these people built some of the oldest existing free-standing structures in the world in the form of the megalithic Ġgantija temples on Gozo; other early temples include those at Ħaġar Qim and Mnajdra.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The temples have distinctive architecture, typically a complex trefoil design, and were used from 4000 to 2500 BC.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Tentative information suggests that animal sacrifices were made to the goddess of fertility, whose statue is now in the National Museum of Archaeology in Valletta.
[src:malta/malta-p01] These may have been caused by wooden-wheeled carts eroding soft limestone.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The culture apparently disappeared from the islands around 2500 BC, possibly due to famine or disease.
[src:malta/malta-p01] After 2500 BC, the Maltese Islands were depopulated for several decades until an influx of Bronze Age immigrants, a culture that cremated its dead and introduced smaller megalithic structures called dolmens.
[src:malta/malta-p01] They are claimed to belong to a population certainly different from that which built the previous megalithic temples.
[src:malta/malta-p01] It is presumed the population arrived from Sicily because of the similarity of Maltese dolmens to some small constructions found there.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Phoenician traders colonised the islands under the name Ann (𐤀𐤍𐤍‎, ʾnn) sometime after 1000 BC as a stop on their trade routes from the eastern Mediterranean to Cornwall.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Their seat of government was apparently at Mdina, which shared the island's name; the primary port was at Cospicua on the Grand Harbour, which they called Maleth.
[src:malta/malta-p01] After the fall of Phoenicia in 332 BC, the area came under the control of Carthage.
[src:malta/malta-p01] During this time, the people on Malta mainly cultivated olives and carob and produced textiles.
[src:malta/malta-p01] During the First Punic War, the island was conquered by Roman general Marcus Atilius Regulus in harsh fighting.
[src:malta/malta-p01] After the failure of his expedition, the island fell back in the hands of Carthage, only to be conquered again during the Second Punic War in 218 BC by the Roman consul Tiberius Sempronius Longus.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta became a *Foederata Civitas*, a designation that meant it was exempt from paying tribute or the rule of Roman law, and fell within the jurisdiction of the province of Sicily.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Its capital at Mdina was renamed Melita after the Greek and Roman name for the island.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Punic influence, however, remained vibrant on the islands with Cippi of Melqart, pivotal in deciphering the Punic language, dedicated in the second century BC.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Local Roman coinage, which ceased in the first century BC, indicates the slow pace of the island's Romanisation: the last locally minted coins still bear inscriptions in Ancient Greek and Punic motifs, showing the resistance of the Greek and Punic cultures.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In the second century, Emperor Hadrian upgraded the status of Malta to a municipium or free town: the island's local affairs were administered by four duumvirs and a municipal senate, while a Roman procurator living in Mdina represented the proconsul of Sicily.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In AD 58, Paul the Apostle and Luke the Evangelist were shipwrecked on the islands.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Paul remained for three months, preaching the Christian faith.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The island is mentioned at the Acts of the Apostles as Melitene (Ancient Greek: Μελιτήνη).
[src:malta/malta-p01] In 395, when the Roman Empire was divided for the last time at the death of Theodosius I, Malta, following Sicily, fell under the control of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:malta/malta-p01] During the Migration Period as the Western Roman Empire declined, Malta was conquered or occupied a number of times.
[src:malta/malta-p01] From 454 to 464 the islands were subdued by the Vandals, and after 464 by the Ostrogoths.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In 533, Belisarius, on his way to conquer the Vandal Kingdom in North Africa, reunited the islands under Imperial (Eastern) rule.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Little is known about the Byzantine rule in Malta: the island depended on the theme of Sicily and had Greek governors and a small Greek garrison.
[src:malta/malta-p01] While the bulk of population continued to be constituted by the old, Latinized dwellers, during this period its religious allegiance oscillated between the Pope and the Patriarch of Constantinople.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The Byzantine rule introduced Greek families to the Maltese collective.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta remained under the Byzantine Empire until 870, when it was conquered by the Arabs.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta became involved in the Arab–Byzantine wars, and the conquest of Malta is closely linked with that of Sicily that began in 827 after Admiral Euphemius' betrayal of his fellow Byzantines, requesting that the Aghlabids invade the island.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The Arab Agricultural Revolution introduced new irrigation, cotton, and some fruits.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The Siculo-Arabic language was adopted on the island from Sicily; it eventually evolved into the Maltese language.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The Normans attacked Malta in 1091, as part of their conquest of Sicily.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The Norman leader, Roger I of Sicily, was welcomed by Christian captives, though contrary to myth he did not tear off a portion of his checkered red-and-white banner and present it to the Maltese in gratitude for having fought on his behalf, forming the basis of the modern flag of Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta became part of the newly formed Kingdom of Sicily, which also covered the island of Sicily and the southern Italian Peninsula.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The Catholic Church was reinstated as the state religion, with Malta under the See of Palermo, and some Norman architecture sprang up around Malta, especially in its ancient capital Mdina.
[src:malta/malta-p01] King Tancred made Malta a fief of the kingdom and installed a Count of Malta in 1192.
[src:malta/malta-p01] As the islands were much desired due to their strategic importance, it was during this time that the men of Malta were militarised to fend off attempted conquest; early Counts were skilled Genoese privateers.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The kingdom passed on to the Hohenstaufen dynasty from 1194 until 1266.
[src:malta/malta-p01] As Emperor Frederick II began to reorganise his Sicilian kingdom, Western culture and religion started to exert their influence more intensely.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta was declared a county and a marquisate, but its trade was totally ruined.
[src:malta/malta-p01] For a long time it remained solely a fortified garrison.
[src:malta/malta-p01] A mass expulsion of Arabs occurred in 1224, and the entire Christian male population of Celano in Abruzzo was deported to Malta in the same year.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In 1249 Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor, decreed that all remaining Muslims be expelled from Malta or compelled to convert.
[src:malta/malta-p01] For a brief period, the kingdom passed to the Capetian House of Anjou, but high taxes made the dynasty unpopular in Malta, due in part to Charles of Anjou's war against the Republic of Genoa, and the island of Gozo was sacked in 1275.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta was ruled by the House of Barcelona, the ruling dynasty of the Crown of Aragon, from 1282 to 1409, with the Aragonese aiding the Maltese insurgents in the Sicilian Vespers in the naval battle in Grand Harbour in 1283.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Relatives of the kings of Aragon ruled the island until 1409 when it formally passed to the Crown of Aragon.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Early on in the Aragonese ascendancy, the sons of the monarchs received the title Count of Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p01] During this time much of the local nobility was created.
[src:malta/malta-p01] By 1397, however, the bearing of the comital title reverted to a feudal basis, with two families fighting over the distinction.
[src:malta/malta-p01] This led King Martin I of Sicily to abolish the title.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The dispute over the title returned when the title was reinstated a few years later and the Maltese, led by the local nobility, rose up against Count Gonsalvo Monroy.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Although they opposed the Count, the Maltese voiced their loyalty to the Sicilian Crown, which so impressed King Alfonso V that he did not punish the people for their rebellion.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Instead, he promised never to grant the title to a third party and incorporated it back into the crown.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The city of Mdina was given the title of *Città Notabile*.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In September 1429, Hafsid Berbers attempted to capture Malta but were repelled by the Maltese.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The invaders pillaged the countryside and took about 3,000 inhabitants as slaves.
[src:malta/malta-p01] On 23 March 1530, Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor, gave the islands to the Knights Hospitaller under the leadership of Frenchman Philippe Villiers de L'Isle-Adam, in perpetual lease for which they had to pay an annual tribute of a single Maltese Falcon.
[src:malta/malta-p01] These knights, a military religious order also known as the Order of St John and later as the Knights of Malta, had been driven out of Rhodes by the Ottoman Empire in 1522.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The Knights Hospitaller ruled Malta and Gozo between 1530 and 1798.
[src:malta/malta-p01] During this period, the strategic and military importance of the island grew greatly as the small yet efficient fleet of the Order of Saint John launched their attacks from this new base targeting the shipping lanes of the Ottoman territories around the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In 1551, the population of the island of Gozo (around 5,000 people) were enslaved by Barbary pirates and taken to the Barbary Coast in North Africa.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The knights, led by Frenchman Jean Parisot de Valette, withstood the Great Siege of Malta by the Ottomans in 1565.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The knights, with the help of Portuguese, Spanish and Maltese forces, repelled the attack.
[src:malta/malta-p01] After the siege they decided to increase Malta's fortifications, particularly in the inner-harbour area, where the new city of Valletta, named in honour of Valette, was built.
[src:malta/malta-p01] They also established watchtowers along the coasts – the Wignacourt, Lascaris and De Redin towers – named after the Grand Masters who ordered the work.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The Knights saw the completion of many architectural and cultural projects, including the embellishment of Città Vittoriosa (modern Birgu) and the construction of new cities including Città Rohan (modern Ħaż-Żebbuġ).
[src:malta/malta-p01] However, by the late 1700s the power of the Knights had declined.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The Knights' reign ended when Napoleon captured Malta on his way to Egypt during the French Revolutionary Wars in 1798.
[src:malta/malta-p01] During 12–18 June 1798, Napoleon resided at the Palazzo Parisio in Valletta.
[src:malta/malta-p01] He reformed national administration with the creation of a Government Commission, twelve municipalities, a public finance administration, the abolition of all feudal rights and privileges, the abolition of slavery and the granting of freedom to all Turkish and Jewish slaves.
[src:malta/malta-p01] On the judicial level, a family code was framed and twelve judges were nominated.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Public education was organised along principles laid down by Bonaparte himself, providing for primary and secondary education.
[src:malta/malta-p01] He then sailed for Egypt, leaving a substantial garrison in Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The French forces left behind became unpopular with the Maltese, due particularly to the French forces' hostility towards Catholicism and pillaging of local churches to fund war efforts.
[src:malta/malta-p01] French financial and religious policies so angered the Maltese that they rebelled, forcing the French to depart.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Great Britain, along with the Kingdom of Naples and the Kingdom of Sicily, sent ammunition and aid to the Maltese, and Britain also sent its navy, which blockaded the islands.
[src:malta/malta-p01] On 28 October 1798, Captain Sir Alexander Ball successfully completed negotiations with the French garrison on Gozo for a surrender and transfer of the island to the British.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The British transferred the island to the locals that day, and it was administered by Archpriest Saverio Cassar on behalf of Ferdinand III of Sicily.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Gozo remained independent until Cassar was removed by the British in 1801.
[src:malta/malta-p01] General Claude-Henri Belgrand de Vaubois surrendered his French forces in 1800.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Maltese leaders presented the main island to Sir Alexander Ball, asking that the island become a British Dominion.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The Maltese people created a Declaration of Rights in which they agreed to come "under the protection and sovereignty of the King of the free people, His Majesty the King of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland".
[src:malta/malta-p01] In 1814, as part of the Treaty of Paris, Malta officially became a part of the British Empire and was used as a shipping way-station and fleet headquarters.
[src:malta/malta-p01] After the Suez Canal opened in 1869, Malta's position halfway between the Strait of Gibraltar and Egypt proved to be its main asset, and it was considered an important stop on the way to India, a central trade route for the British.
[src:malta/malta-p01] A Turkish Military Cemetery was commissioned by Sultan Abdul Aziz and built between 1873 and 1874 for the fallen Ottoman soldiers of the Great Siege of Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Between 1915 and 1918, during the First World War, Malta became known as *the Nurse of the Mediterranean* due to the large number of wounded soldiers who were accommodated there.
[src:malta/malta-p01] On 7 June 1919, the Maltese public rioted in response to a cost-of-living crisis; British troops eventually managed to suppress the riots, killing four in the process.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The event, known as Sette Giugno ("7 June"), is commemorated every year and is one of five National Days.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Until the Second World War, Maltese politics was dominated by the Language Question fought out by Italophone and Anglophone parties.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Before the Second World War, Valletta was the location of the Royal Navy's Mediterranean fleet headquarters; however, despite Winston Churchill's objections, the command was moved to Alexandria, Egypt, in 1937 out of fear that it was too susceptible to air attacks from Europe.
[src:malta/malta-p01] During the war, Malta played an important role for the Allies; being a British colony, situated close to Sicily and the Axis shipping lanes, Malta was bombarded by the Italian and German air forces.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta was used by the British to launch attacks on the Italian Navy and had a submarine base.
[src:malta/malta-p01] It was also used as a listening post, intercepting German radio messages including Enigma traffic.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The bravery of the Maltese people during the second siege of Malta moved King George VI to award the George Cross to Malta on a collective basis on 15 April 1942.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Some historians argue that the award caused Britain to incur disproportionate losses in defending Malta, as British credibility would have suffered if Malta had surrendered, as British forces in Singapore had done.
[src:malta/malta-p01] A depiction of the George Cross now appears on the Flag of Malta and the country's arms.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta achieved its independence as the State of Malta on 21 September 1964 (Independence Day).
[src:malta/malta-p01] Under its 1964 constitution, Malta initially retained Elizabeth II as Queen of Malta and thus head of state, with a governor-general exercising executive authority on her behalf.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In 1971, the Malta Labour Party led by Dom Mintoff won the general elections, resulting in Malta declaring itself a republic on 13 December 1974 (Republic Day) within the Commonwealth.
[src:malta/malta-p01] A defence agreement was signed soon after independence, and after being re-negotiated in 1972, expired on 31 March 1979 (Freedom Day).
[src:malta/malta-p01] Upon its expiry, the British base closed and lands formerly controlled by the British were given to the Maltese government.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In the aftermath of the departure of the remaining British troops in 1979, the country intensified its participation in the Non-Aligned Movement.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta adopted a policy of neutrality in 1980.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In that same year, three of Malta's sites, including the capital Valletta, were inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In 1989, Malta was the venue of a summit between US President George H.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev, their first face-to-face encounter, which signalled the end of the Cold War.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta International Airport was inaugurated and became fully operational on 25 March 1992, boosting the local aircraft and tourism industry.
[src:malta/malta-p01] A referendum on joining the European Union was held on 8 March 2003, with 53.65% in favour.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta joined the European Union on 1 May 2004 and the eurozone on 1 January 2008.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta is an archipelago in the central Mediterranean (in its eastern basin), some 80 km (50 mi) from southern Italy across the Malta Channel.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Only the three largest islands—Malta (Maltese: *Malta*), Gozo (*Għawdex*), and Comino (*Kemmuna*)—are inhabited.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The islands of the archipelago lie on the Malta plateau, a shallow shelf formed from the high points of a land bridge between Sicily and North Africa that became isolated as sea levels rose after the last ice age.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The archipelago is located on the African tectonic plate.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta was considered an island of North Africa for centuries.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Numerous bays along the indented coastline of the islands provide good harbours.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The landscape consists of low hills with terraced fields.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The highest point in Malta is Ta' Dmejrek, at 253 m (830 ft), near Dingli.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Although there are some small rivers at times of high rainfall, there are no permanent rivers or lakes on Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p01] However, some watercourses have fresh water running all year round at Baħrija near Ras ir-Raħeb, at l-Imtaħleb and San Martin, and at Lunzjata Valley in Gozo.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Phytogeographically, Malta belongs to the Liguro-Tyrrhenian province of the Mediterranean region within the Boreal Kingdom.
[src:malta/malta-p01] According to the WWF, the territory of Malta belongs to the terrestrial ecoregion of Tyrrhenian–Adriatic sclerophyllous and mixed forests.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta has a Mediterranean climate (Köppen climate classification *Csa*), with mild winters and hot summers, hotter in the inland areas.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Rain occurs mainly in autumn and winter, with summer being generally dry.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The average yearly temperature is around 23 °C (73 °F) during the day and 15.5 °C (59.9 °F) at night.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In the coldest month – January – the typical maximum temperature ranges from 12 to 18 °C (54 to 64 °F) during the day and minimum 6 to 12 °C (43 to 54 °F) at night.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In the warmest month – August – the typical maximum temperature ranges from 28 to 34 °C (82 to 93 °F) during the day and minimum 20 to 24 °C (68 to 75 °F) at night.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Amongst all capitals in the continent of Europe, Valletta – the capital of Malta has the warmest winters, with average temperatures of around 15 to 16 °C (59 to 61 °F) during the day and 9 to 10 °C (48 to 50 °F) at night in the period January–February.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In March and December average temperatures are around 17 °C (63 °F) during the day and 11 °C (52 °F) at night.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Large fluctuations in temperature are rare.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Snow is very rare, although snowfalls have been recorded in the last century, the last one in 2014.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The average annual sea temperature is 20 °C (68 °F), from 15–16 °C (59–61 °F) in February to 26 °C (79 °F) in August.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In the six months from June to November, the average sea temperature exceeds 20 °C (68 °F).
[src:malta/malta-p01] The annual average relative humidity is high, averaging 75%, ranging from 65% in July (morning: 78% evening: 53%) to 80% in December (morning: 83% evening: 73%).
[src:malta/malta-p01] Sunshine duration hours total around 3,000 per year, from an average 5.2 hours of sunshine duration per day in December to an average above 12 hours in July.
[src:malta/malta-p01] This is about double that of cities in the northern half of Europe, for comparison: London – 1,461; however, in winter it has up to four times more sunshine; for comparison: in December, London has 37 hours of sunshine whereas Malta has above 160.
[src:malta/malta-p01] According to Eurostat, Malta is composed of two larger urban zones nominally referred to as "Valletta" (the main island of Malta) and "Gozo".
[src:malta/malta-p01] The main urban area covers the entire main island, with a population of around 400,000.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The core of the urban area, the *greater city* of Valletta, has a population of 205,768.
[src:malta/malta-p01] According to the data from 2020 by Eurostat, the Functional Urban Area and metropolitan region covered the whole island and has a population of 480,134.
[src:malta/malta-p01] According to the United Nations, about 95 percent of the area of Malta is urban and the number grows every year.
[src:malta/malta-p01] According to ESPON and EU Commission studies, "the whole territory of Malta constitutes a single urban region".
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta, with area of 316 km2 (122 sq mi) and population of over 0.5 million, is one of the most densely populated countries worldwide.
[src:malta/malta-p01] It is in some sources referred to as a city-state.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Sometimes Malta is listed in rankings concerning cities or metropolitan areas.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta contains only 4.6 square kilometres (1.8 sq mi) of naturally regenerating forest, characterised by mature trees with a height of 2 to 5 metres (6 ft 7 in to 16 ft 5 in).
[src:malta/malta-p01] The overall area occupied by trees is estimated to be 32 square kilometres (12 sq mi), which constitutes approximately 1.44% of the total land area of the archipelago.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The Maltese islands are also home to a wide diversity of indigenous, sub-endemic and endemic plants.
[src:malta/malta-p01] They feature many traits typical of a Mediterranean climate, such as drought resistance.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Endemic plants include the national flower *widnet il-baħar* (*Cheirolophus crassifolius*), *sempreviva ta' Malta* (*Helichrysum panormitanum* subsp.
[src:malta/malta-p01] *melitense*), *żigland t' Għawdex* (*Hyoseris frutescens*) and *ġiżi ta' Malta* (*Matthiola incana* subsp.
[src:malta/malta-p01] *melitensis*) while sub-endemics include *kromb il-baħar* (*Jacobaea maritima* subsp.
[src:malta/malta-p01] *sicula*) and *xkattapietra* (*Micromeria microphylla*).
[src:malta/malta-p01] The biodiversity of Malta is severely endangered by habitat loss, invasive species, and human intervention.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta is a republic whose parliamentary system and public administration are closely modelled on the Westminster system.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The unicameral parliament is made up of the president of Malta and the House of Representatives (Maltese: *Kamra tad-Deputati*).
[src:malta/malta-p01] The House of Representatives has 65 members, elected for a five-year term in 13 five-seat electoral divisions, called *distretti elettorali*, with constitutional amendments that allow for mechanisms to establish strict proportionality amongst seats and votes of political parliamentary groups.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Members of the House of Representatives are elected by direct universal suffrage through single transferable vote every five years, unless the House is dissolved earlier by the president either on the advice of the prime minister or through a motion of no confidence.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta had the second-highest voter turnout in the world (and the highest for nations without mandatory voting), based on election turnout in national lower house elections from 1960 to 1995.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The President of Malta, a largely ceremonial position, is appointed for a five-year term by a resolution of the House of Representatives carried by a simple majority.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Myriam Spiteri Debono was elected on 27 March 2024 President of the Republic by members of parliament in an indirect election.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The 80th article of the Constitution of Malta provides that the president appoint as prime minister "the member of the House of Representatives who, in his judgment, is best able to command the support of a majority of the members of that House".
[src:malta/malta-p01] Maltese politics is a two-party system dominated by the Labour Party (Maltese: *Partit Laburista*), a centre-left social democratic party, and the Nationalist Party (Maltese: *Partit Nazzjonalista*), a centre-right Christian democratic party.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The Labour Party has been the governing party since 2013 and is currently led by Prime Minister Robert Abela, who has been in office since 13 January 2020.
[src:malta/malta-p01] There are also a number of small political parties in Malta that have no parliamentary representation.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Corruption, money laundering, and government maladministration in Malta have significantly increased since the Labour Party returned to power.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In fact, Malta's record of clean governance has decreased since 2013, and the country is now considered one of the worst EU member states in tackling corruption according to Transparency International.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The same association reported that Malta dropped to its lowest ever ranking of 65th place in a report published in February 2025.
[src:malta/malta-p01] According to International IDEA's Global State of Democracy (GSoD) Indices and Democracy Tracker, Malta performs in the mid to high range on overall democratic measures, with particular weaknesses in the absence of corruption and civic engagement.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta has had a system of local government since 1993, based on the European Charter of Local Self-Government.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The country is divided into six regions (one of them being Gozo), with each region having its own Regional Council, serving as the intermediate level between local government and national government.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The regions are divided into local councils, of which there are currently 68 (54 in Malta and 14 in Gozo).
[src:malta/malta-p01] The six districts (five on Malta and the sixth being Gozo) serve primarily statistical purposes.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Each council is made up of a number of councillors (from 5 to 13, depending on and relative to the population they represent).
[src:malta/malta-p01] A mayor and a deputy mayor are elected by and from the councillors.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The executive secretary, who is appointed by the council, is the executive, administrative and financial head of the council.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Councillors are elected every four years through the single transferable vote.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Due to system reforms, no elections were held before 2012.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Since then, elections have been held every two years for an alternating half of the councils.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Additionally, a number of individual towns and villages in the Republic of Malta have sister cities.
[src:malta/malta-p01] The objectives of the Armed Forces of Malta (AFM) are to maintain a military organisation with the primary aim of defending the islands' integrity according to the defence roles as set by the government in an efficient and cost-effective manner.
[src:malta/malta-p01] This is achieved by emphasising the maintenance of Malta's territorial waters and airspace integrity.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta's search-and-rescue area extends from east of Tunisia to west of Crete, an area of around 250,000 km2 (97,000 sq mi).
[src:malta/malta-p01] As a military organisation, the AFM provides backup support to the Malta Police Force (MPF) and other government departments/agencies in situations as required in an organised, disciplined manner in the event of national emergencies (such as natural disasters) or internal security and bomb disposal.
[src:malta/malta-p01] In 2020, Malta signed and ratified the UN treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta is regarded as one of the most LGBT-supportive countries in the world, and was the first nation in the European Union to prohibit conversion therapy.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta also constitutionally bans discrimination based on disability.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Maltese legislation recognises both civil and canonical (ecclesiastical) marriages.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Annulments by the ecclesiastical and civil courts are unrelated and are not necessarily mutually endorsed.
[src:malta/malta-p01] Malta voted in favour of divorce legislation in a referendum held on 28 May 2011.
[src:malta/malta-p01] It and Poland are the only European Union members with near-total bans on the procedure.
[src:malta/malta-p01] There are no exceptions for rape or incest.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta is classified as an advanced economy according to the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta's major resources are limestone, a favourable geographic location and a productive labour force.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta produces only about 20 percent of its food needs, has limited fresh water supplies because of the drought in the summer, and has no domestic energy sources, aside from the potential for solar energy from its plentiful sunlight.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The economy is dependent on foreign trade (serving as a freight trans-shipment point), manufacturing (especially electronics and textiles), and tourism.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Film production has contributed to the Maltese economy.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Access to biocapacity in Malta is below the world average.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In 2024, Malta had 0.42 global hectares of biocapacity per person within its territory, contrasted with a global average of 1.6 hectares (4.0 acres) per person.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Additionally, residents of Malta exhibited an ecological footprint of consumption of 5.12 global hectares of biocapacity per person, resulting in a sizable biocapacity deficit.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In preparation for Malta's membership in the European Union, which it joined on 1 May 2004, it privatised some state-controlled firms and liberalised markets.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta has a financial regulator, the Malta Financial Services Authority (MFSA), with a strong business development mindset, and the country has been successful in attracting gaming businesses, aircraft and ship registration, credit-card issuing banking licences and also fund administration.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta has made strong headway in implementing EU Financial Services Directives including UCITs IV and Alternative Investment Fund Managers (AIFMs).
[src:malta/malta-p02] As a base for alternative asset managers who must comply with new directives, Malta has attracted a number of key players including IDS, Iconic Funds, Apex Fund Services and TMF/Customs House.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta does not have an annual property tax; however, it does still tax property in transactions.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Maltese real estate sales totalled over €320 million in May 2025, the second highest monthly total since 2023.
[src:malta/malta-p02] According to Eurostat data, Maltese nominal GDP per capita stood at €39,350 in 2024, 9% higher than the EU average.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The National Development and Social Fund from the Individual Investor Programme, a citizenship by investment programme also known as the "citizenship scheme", became a significant income source for the government of Malta, adding €432 million to the budget in 2018.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The two largest commercial banks are Bank of Valletta and HSBC Bank Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Digital banks such as Revolut have also increased in popularity.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Central Bank of Malta (Bank Ċentrali ta' Malta) has two key areas of responsibility: the formulation and implementation of monetary policy and the promotion of a sound and efficient financial system.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Maltese government entered ERM II on 4 May 2005, and adopted the euro as the country's currency on 1 January 2008.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Maltese euro coins feature the Maltese cross on €2 and €1 coins, the coat of arms of Malta on the €0.50, €0.20 and €0.10 coins, and the Mnajdra Temples on the €0.05, €0.02 and €0.01 coins.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta has produced collectors' coins with face value ranging from €10 to €50.
[src:malta/malta-p02] These coins continue an existing national practice of minting of silver and gold commemorative coins.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Unlike normal issues, these coins are not accepted in all the eurozone.
[src:malta/malta-p02] From 1825 until the 2008 introduction of the Euro, the currency was the Maltese lira, also called the pound.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Until 1825 the currency was the Maltese scudo.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta is a popular tourist destination, with 1.6 million tourists per year, three times more tourists visit than there are residents.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Tourism infrastructure has increased dramatically over the years and a number of hotels are present on the island, although overdevelopment and the destruction of traditional housing is of growing concern.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In 2019, Malta had a record year in tourism, recording over 2.1 million tourists in one single year.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In recent years, Malta has advertised itself as a medical tourism destination, and a number of health tourism providers are developing the industry.
[src:malta/malta-p02] However, no Maltese hospital has undergone independent international healthcare accreditation.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta is popular with British medical tourists, pointing Maltese hospitals towards seeking UK-sourced accreditation, such as with the Trent Accreditation Scheme.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Tourism in Malta contributes around 11.6 percent of the country's gross domestic product.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The country's variety of landscapes and destinations has also become a significant draw for filmmakers, earning it the reputation as "the Hollywood of the Mediterranean".
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta signed a co-operation agreement with the European Space Agency (ESA) for more-intensive co-operation in ESA projects.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Malta Council for Science and Technology (MCST) is the civil body responsible for the development of science and technology on an educational and social level.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Most science students in Malta graduate from the University of Malta and are represented by S-Cubed (Science Student's Society), UESA (University Engineering Students Association) and ICTSA (University of Malta ICT Students' Association).
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta was ranked 27th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Owing to the British colonial rule, traffic in Malta drives on the left.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta has a high level of motorisation; according to the National Statistics Office, the number of licensed motor vehicles per 1,000 residents fell from 784 in 2022 to 778 in 2023.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There were 778 licensed motor vehicles per 1,000 residents in 2023.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta has 3,096 kilometres (1,924 mi) of road; as of 2021, 444 kilometres (276 mi) were classified as other rural unpaved roads.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Buses (*xarabank* or *karozza tal-linja*) are the primary method of public transport, established in 1905.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta's vintage buses operated in the Maltese islands up to 2011 and became popular tourist attractions.
[src:malta/malta-p02] To this day they are depicted on many Maltese advertisements and merchandise for tourists.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The bus service underwent extensive reform in July 2011.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The management structure changed from having self-employed drivers driving their own vehicles to a service being offered by a single company through a public tender.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The public tender was won by Arriva Malta, which introduced a fleet of brand new buses, built by King Long especially for service by Arriva Malta and including a smaller fleet of articulated buses brought in from Arriva London.
[src:malta/malta-p02] It also operated two smaller buses for an intra-Valletta route only and 61 nine-metre buses, which were used to ease congestion on high-density routes.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Overall Arriva Malta operated 264 buses.
[src:malta/malta-p02] On 1 January 2014 Arriva ceased operations in Malta due to financial difficulties, having been nationalised as *Malta Public Transport*.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The government chose Autobuses Urbanos de León (Alsa subsidiary) as its preferred bus operator for the country in October 2014.
[src:malta/malta-p02] From October 2022, the bus system is free of charge for residents of Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p02] As of 2021, an underground Malta Metro is being planned, with a projected total cost of €6.2 billion.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There are also two human-made harbours that serve a passenger and car ferry service that connects Ċirkewwa Harbour on Malta and Mġarr Harbour on Gozo.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta International Airport (Ajruport Internazzjonali ta' Malta) is the only airport serving the Maltese islands.
[src:malta/malta-p02] It is built on the land formerly occupied by the RAF Luqa air base.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The former RAF Ta Kali airfield at Ta' Qali houses a national park, stadium, the Crafts Village visitor attraction and the Malta Aviation Museum.
[src:malta/malta-p02] From 1 April 1974 to 30 March 2024, the national airline was Air Malta, which was based at Malta International Airport and operated services to 22 destinations in Europe and North Africa.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The owners of Air Malta were the Government of Malta (98 percent) and private investors (2 percent).
[src:malta/malta-p02] On 31 March 2024, KM Malta Airlines took over as the national airline of Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p02] All former Air Malta Airplanes and other assets were transferred to the new airline, together with the staff.
[src:malta/malta-p02] KM Malta Airlines is based at Malta International Airport and operates services to 18 destinations in Europe.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In June 2019, Ryanair has invested into a fully-fledged airline subsidiary, called Malta Air, operating a low-cost model.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Government of Malta holds one share in the airline.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The mobile penetration rate in Malta exceeded 100% by the end of 2009, reaching 102.1%.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta's mobile sector has used GSM, UMTS (3G), and LTE (4G) technologies.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In early 2012, the government called for a national Fibre to the Home (FttH) network to be built, with a minimum broadband service being upgraded from 4 Mbit/s to 100 Mbit/s.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta relied on coal until 1996 for electricity generation.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In 1992, a new power station was built on the Delimara peninsula in Marsaxlokk.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Originally the Delimara Power Station in 2015 used oil for electricity generation, before being converted to LNG in 2017.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The power station also includes two gasoil-fired plants, which are used as standby power generation capacity during emergencies or lack of other power sources.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Since 2015, the Malta–Sicily interconnector allows Malta to be connected to the European power grid and import a significant share of its electricity.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In 2024, Malta consumed 3106 GWh, of which 970 GWh was imported through the interconnector.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Just 9.2% of Malta's electricity in 2024 was from domestic renewable generation, almost all of which is photovoltaic panels.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There are efforts to boost this renewable generation share to 25% by leveraging offshore platforms and battery storage by 2030 but 9.2% represents a drop in generation share from 2023 when renewables accounted for 10% of the electricity generated.
[src:malta/malta-p02] A waste-to-energy plant that runs off of biogas generated by organic waste is planned to contribute a further 4.5% to the electricity grid as a source of net carbon-neutral energy.
[src:malta/malta-p02] As of the 2021 census, Maltese-born natives make up the majority of the island with 386,280 people out of a total population of 519,562.
[src:malta/malta-p02] However, there are minorities, the largest of which by birthplace were: 15,082 from the United Kingdom, Italy (13,361), India (7,946), Philippines (7,784) and Serbia (5,935).
[src:malta/malta-p02] Among racial origins for the non-Maltese, 58.1% of all identified as Caucasian, 22.2% Asian, 6.3% Arab, 6.0% African, 4.5% Hispanic or Latino and 2.9% more than one race.
[src:malta/malta-p02] As of 2005, 17 percent were aged 14 and under, 68 percent were within the 15–64 age bracket whilst the remaining 13 percent were 65 years and over.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta's population density of 1,282 per square km (3,322/sq mi) is by far the highest in the EU and one of the highest in the world.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Maltese-resident population for 2004 was estimated to make up 97.0 per cent of the total resident population.
[src:malta/malta-p02] All censuses since 1842 have shown a slight excess of females over males.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Population growth has slowed down, from +9.5 per cent between the 1985 and 1995 censuses, to +6.9 per cent between the 1995 and 2005 censuses (a yearly average of +0.7 per cent).
[src:malta/malta-p02] The birth rate stood at 3860 (a decrease of 21.8 per cent from the 1995 census) and the death rate stood at 3025.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Thus, there was a natural population increase of 835 (compared to +888 for 2004, of which over a hundred were foreign residents).
[src:malta/malta-p02] The population's age composition is similar to the age structure prevalent in the EU.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta's old-age-dependency-ratio is expected to continue rising steadily in the coming years.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In 2021, the population of the Maltese Islands stood at 519,562.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The total fertility rate (TFR) as of 2016 was estimated at 1.45 children born/woman, which is below the replacement rate of 2.1.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In 2012, 25.8 per cent of births were to unmarried women.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The life expectancy in 2018 was estimated at 83.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Maltese language (Maltese: *Malti*) is one of the two constitutional languages of Malta and is considered the national language.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The second official language is English and hence laws are enacted both in Maltese and English.
[src:malta/malta-p02] However, article 74 of the Constitution states that "if there is any conflict between the Maltese and the English texts of any law, the Maltese text shall prevail." Many speakers of English use a local dialect, Maltese English.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Maltese is a Semitic language descended from the now extinct Sicilian-Arabic (Siculo-Arabic) dialect (from southern Italy) that developed during the Emirate of Sicily.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Maltese alphabet consists of 30 letters based on the Latin alphabet.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In 2022, Malta National Statistics Office states that 90 percent of the Maltese population has at least a basic knowledge of Maltese, 96 percent of English, 62 percent of Italian, and 20 percent of French.
[src:malta/malta-p02] This widespread knowledge of second languages makes Malta one of the most multilingual countries in the European Union.
[src:malta/malta-p02] A study collecting public opinion on what language was "preferred" discovered that 86 percent of the population preferred Maltese, 12 percent English, and 2 percent Italian.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Italian television channels from Italy-based broadcasters, such as Mediaset and RAI, reach Malta and remain popular.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Maltese Sign Language is used by signers in Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p02] According to the 2021 census, among the population aged 5 and over, the main languages spoken from early childhood were the following.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The predominant religion in Malta is Catholicism.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The second article of the Constitution of Malta establishes Catholicism as the state religion and it is also reflected in various elements of Maltese culture, although there are entrenched provisions for the freedom of religion.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There are more than 360 churches in Malta, Gozo, and Comino, or one church for every 1,000 residents.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The parish church (Maltese: *il-parroċċa* or *il-knisja parrokkjali*) is the architectural and geographic focal point of every Maltese town and village.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta is an Apostolic See; the Acts of the Apostles (Acts 28) tells of how St.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Paul was shipwrecked on the island of "Melite", which many Biblical scholars identify with Malta, an episode dated around AD 60.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Saint Publius is said to have been made Malta's first bishop.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Further evidence of Christian practices and beliefs during the period of Roman persecution appears in catacombs that lie beneath various sites around Malta, including St.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There are also a number of cave churches, including the grotto at Mellieħa, which is a Shrine of the Nativity of Our Lady where, according to legend, St.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Luke painted a picture of the Virgin Mary.
[src:malta/malta-p02] It has been a place of pilgrimage since the medieval period.
[src:malta/malta-p02] For centuries, the Church in Malta was subordinate to the Diocese of Palermo, except when it was under Charles of Anjou, who appointed bishops for Malta, as did – on rare occasions – the Spanish and later, the Knights.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Since 1808 all bishops of Malta have been Maltese.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The patron saints of Malta are Saint Paul, Saint Publius, and Saint Agatha.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Although not a patron saint, St George Preca (San Ġorġ Preca) is greatly revered as the first canonised Maltese saint.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Various Catholic religious orders are present in Malta, including the Jesuits, Franciscans, Dominicans, Carmelites and Little Sisters of the Poor.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There exists a considerable minority of Orthodox Christians in Malta, of which there are 16,457, according to the 2021 census; the number may include both Eastern Orthodox and Oriental Orthodox Christians.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There are a small number of parishes belonging to each autocephalous Church, typically one for each.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There are Greek, Russian, Serbian, Romanian, and Bulgarian Orthodox parishes located around Malta, mainly in Valletta.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Most congregants of the local Protestant churches are not Maltese; their congregations mainly draw on vacationers and British retirees living in the country.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There are also a Seventh-day Adventist church in Birkirkara, and a New Apostolic Church congregation founded in 1983 in Gwardamangia.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There are approximately 600 Jehovah's Witnesses.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Latter-day Saints is also represented with 241 members in 1 congregation in Mosta.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Jewish population of Malta reached its peak in the Middle Ages under Norman rule.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In 1479, Malta and Sicily came under Aragonese rule and the Alhambra Decree of 1492 forced all Jews to leave the country.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Today, there are two Jewish congregations.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In 2019 the Jewish community in Malta gathered around 150 persons, slightly more than the 120 (of which 80 were active) estimated in 2003, and mostly elderly.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Many among the newer generations decided to settle abroad, including in England and Israel.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Most contemporary Maltese Jews are Sephardi, however, an Ashkenazi prayer book is used.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In 2013 the Chabad Jewish Centre in Malta was founded.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There is one purpose-built Muslim mosque, the Mariam Al-Batool Mosque, although there are also a few improvised mosques located in Muslim homes spread around the island.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The 2021 census recorded 17,454 Muslims, of which 1,746 were Maltese citizens.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Zen Buddhism and the Baháʼí Faith claim some 40 members.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In a survey held by *Malta Today*, the overwhelming majority of the Maltese population adheres to Christianity (95.2%) with Catholicism as the main denomination (93.9%); 4.5% of the population declared themselves either atheist or agnostic, one of the lowest figures in Europe.
[src:malta/malta-p02] According to a 2019 Eurobarometer survey, 83% of the population identified as Catholic.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The number of atheists has doubled from 2014 to 2018.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The 2015 edition of the annual Freedom of Thought Report from the International Humanist and Ethical Union, asserted Malta was in the category of "severe discrimination", alongside seven other EU countries.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In 2016, following the abolishment of blasphemy law, Malta was shifted to the category of "systematic discrimination" (same as most EU countries).
[src:malta/malta-p02] Historically a land of emigration, since the early 21st century Malta has seen a significant increase in net migration; the foreign-born population has grown nearly eightfold between 2005 and 2020.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Most of the foreign community in Malta consists of active or retired British nationals and their dependents, centred on Sliema and surrounding suburbs.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Other smaller foreign groups include Italians, Libyans, and Serbians, many of whom have assimilated into the Maltese nation over the decades.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta is also home to a large number of foreign workers who migrated to the island for economic opportunity.
[src:malta/malta-p02] This migration was driven predominantly in the early 21st century, when the Maltese economy was steadily booming yet the cost and quality of living on the island remained relatively stable.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In recent years however the local Maltese housing index has doubled pushing property and rental prices to very high and almost unaffordable levels.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Consequently, some expats in Malta have seen their relative financial fortunes decline, with others relocating to other European countries altogether.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Since the late 20th century, Malta has become a transit country for migration routes from Africa towards Europe.
[src:malta/malta-p02] As a member of the European Union and the Schengen Agreement, Malta is bound by the Dublin Regulation to process all claims for asylum by those asylum seekers that enter EU territory for the first time in Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p02] However, irregular migrants who land in Malta are subject to a compulsory detention policy, being held in several camps organised by the Armed Forces of Malta (AFM), including those near Ħal Far and Ħal Safi.
[src:malta/malta-p02] On 8 September 2020, Amnesty International criticised Malta for "illegal tactics" in the Mediterranean, against immigrants who were attempting to cross from North Africa.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The reports claimed that the government's approach might have led to avoidable deaths.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In January 2014, Malta started granting citizenship for a €650,000 contribution plus investments, contingent on residence and criminal background checks.
[src:malta/malta-p02] This "golden passport" citizenship scheme has been criticized as a fraudulent act by the Maltese Government.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Concerns as to whether the Maltese citizenship scheme is allowing an influx of such individuals into the greater European Union have been raised by both the public as well as the European Council on multiple occasions.
[src:malta/malta-p02] On 29 April 2025, the European Court of Justice ruled that Malta may no longer sell citizenship through its 'golden passports' scheme.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In the 19th century, most emigration from Malta was to North Africa and the Middle East, although rates of return migration to Malta were high.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In the 20th century, most emigrants went to destinations in the New World, particularly to Australia, Canada, and the United States.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Post Second World War, Malta's Emigration Department would assist emigrants with the cost of their travel.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Between 1948 and 1967, 30 percent of the population emigrated.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Between 1946 and the late-1970s, over 140,000 people left Malta on the assisted passage scheme, with 57.6% migrating to Australia, 22% to the UK, 13% to Canada and 7% to the United States.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Emigration dropped dramatically after the mid-1970s and has since ceased to be a social phenomenon of significance.
[src:malta/malta-p02] However, since Malta joined the EU in 2004 expatriate communities emerged in a number of European countries, particularly in Belgium and Luxembourg.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Primary schooling has been compulsory since 1946; secondary education up to the age of sixteen was made compulsory in 1971.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The state and the Catholic Church provide education free of charge, both running a number of schools in Malta and Gozo.
[src:malta/malta-p02] As of 2006, state schools are organised into networks known as Colleges and incorporate kindergarten schools, primary and secondary schools.
[src:malta/malta-p02] A number of private schools are run in Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Catherine's High School, Pembroke offers an International Foundation Course for students wishing to learn English before entering mainstream education.
[src:malta/malta-p02] As of 2008, there are two international schools, Verdala International School and QSI Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The state pays a portion of the teachers' salary in Church schools.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Education in Malta is based on the British model.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Pupils sit for SEC O-level examinations at the age of 16, with passes obligatory in mathematics, a minimum of one science subject, English and Maltese.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Pupils may opt to continue studying at a sixth form college for two years, at the end of which students sit for the matriculation examination.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Subject to their performance, students may then apply for an undergraduate degree or diploma.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The adult literacy rate is 99.5 per cent.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Maltese and English are both used to teach pupils at the primary and secondary school level, and both languages are also compulsory subjects.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Public schools tend to use both Maltese and English in a balanced manner.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Private schools prefer to use English for teaching, as is also the case with most departments of the University of Malta; this has a limiting effect on the capacity and development of the Maltese language.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Of the total number of pupils studying a first foreign language at secondary level, 51 per cent take Italian whilst 38 per cent take French.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Other choices include German, Russian, Spanish, Latin, Chinese and Arabic.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta is also a popular destination to study the English language, attracting over 83,000 students in 2019.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta has a long history of providing publicly funded health care.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The first hospital recorded in the country was already functioning by 1372.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Today, Malta has both a public healthcare system, where healthcare is free at the point of delivery, and a private healthcare system.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta has a strong general practitioner-delivered primary care base and the public hospitals provide secondary and tertiary care.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Maltese Ministry of Health advises foreign residents to take out private medical insurance.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta also boasts voluntary organisations such as Alpha Medical (Advanced Care), the Emergency Fire & Rescue Unit (E.F.R.U.), St John Ambulance and Red Cross Malta who provide first aid/nursing services during events involving crowds.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Mater Dei hospital, Malta's primary hospital, opened in 2007.
[src:malta/malta-p02] It has one of the largest medical buildings in Europe.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The University of Malta has a medical school and a Faculty of Health Sciences.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Medical Association of Malta represents practitioners of the medical profession.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Foundation Programme followed in the UK has been introduced in Malta to stem the 'brain drain' of newly graduated physicians to the British Isles.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The culture of Malta reflects the various cultures that have come into contact with the Maltese Islands throughout the centuries.
[src:malta/malta-p02] A 2010 Charities Aid Foundation study found that the Maltese were the most generous people in the world, with 83% contributing to charity.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Maltese folktales include various stories about mysterious creatures and supernatural events.
[src:malta/malta-p02] These were most comprehensively compiled by the scholar (and pioneer in Maltese archaeology) Manwel Magri in his core criticism "*Ħrejjef Missirijietna*" ("Fables from our Forefathers").
[src:malta/malta-p02] This collection of material inspired subsequent researchers and academics to gather traditional tales, fables and legends from all over the Archipelago.
[src:malta/malta-p02] While giants, witches, and dragons feature in many of the stories, some contain entirely Maltese creatures like the Kaw kaw, Il-Belliegħa and L-Imħalla among others.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Traditional Maltese proverbs reveal cultural importance of childbearing and fertility: "*iż-żwieġ mingħajr tarbija ma fihx tgawdija*" (a childless marriage cannot be a happy one).
[src:malta/malta-p02] This is a belief that Malta shares with many other Mediterranean cultures.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In Maltese folktales the local variant of the classic closing formula, "and they all lived happily ever after" is "*u għammru u tgħammru, u spiċċat*" (and they lived together, and they had children together, and the tale is finished).
[src:malta/malta-p02] Rural Malta shares in common with the Mediterranean society a number of superstitions regarding fertility, menstruation, and pregnancy, including the avoidance of cemeteries leading up to childbirth, and avoiding the preparation of certain foods during menses.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Pregnant women are encouraged to satisfy their food cravings, out of fear that their unborn child will bear a representational birth mark (Maltese: *xewqa*, literally "desire" or "craving").
[src:malta/malta-p02] Maltese and Sicilian folk tradition includes beliefs thought to predict the sex of an unborn child, such as using the moon cycle, the way the baby is carried, or the motion of a ring suspended over the abdomen.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Traditionally, Maltese newborns were baptised as soon as possible.
[src:malta/malta-p02] At baptismal feasts, traditional sweets and liqueurs associated with the occasion included *biskuttini tal-magħmudija*, *torta tal-marmorata*, and *rożolin*.
[src:malta/malta-p02] On a child's first birthday, in a tradition that still survives today, Maltese parents would organise a game known as *il-quċċija*, where a variety of symbolic objects would be randomly placed around the child.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Whichever object the child shows the most interest in is said to reveal the child's path and fortunes in adulthood.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Traditional Maltese weddings included a bridal procession from the bride's home to the parish church, often accompanied by singers performing *il-ġilwa* beneath a decorated canopy.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Historically, Maltese women wore the *għonnella*, a traditional form of dress.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In modern times, couples are typically married in churches or chapels, followed by wedding receptions, although some incorporate elements of traditional customs into their celebrations.
[src:malta/malta-p02] A renewed interest in historical wedding traditions was demonstrated in 2007, when a large-scale 16th-century style wedding reenactment was held in Żurrieq, attracting both locals and tourists.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Local festivals, similar to those in Southern Italy, are commonplace in Malta and Gozo, celebrating weddings, christenings and, most prominently, saints' days.
[src:malta/malta-p02] On saints' days, in the morning, the *festa* reaches its apex with a High Mass featuring a sermon on the life and achievements of the patron saint.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In the evening, a statue of the religious patron is taken around the local streets in solemn procession, with the faithful following in prayer.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The atmosphere of religious devotion is preceded by several days of celebration and revelry: band marches, fireworks, and late-night parties.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The largest festa is possibly that of the Assumption of Mary, which is celebrated in 8 parishes on 15 August and in 2 other parishes the following Sunday.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Carnival (Maltese: *il-karnival ta' Malta*) has had an important place on the cultural calendar.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Holy Week (Maltese: *il-Ġimgħa Mqaddsa*) starts on Palm Sunday (*Ħadd il-Palm*) and ends on Easter Sunday (*Ħadd il-Għid*).
[src:malta/malta-p02] Mnarja, or l-Imnarja (pronounced *lim-nar-ya*) is one of the most important dates on the Maltese cultural calendar.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Officially, it is a national festival dedicated to the feast of Saints Peter and Paul.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Its roots can be traced back to the pagan Roman feast of *Luminaria* (literally, "the illumination"), when torches and bonfires lit up the early summer night of 29 June.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The festivities still commence today with the reading of the *"bandu"*, an official governmental announcement, which has been read on this day in Malta since the 16th century.
[src:malta/malta-p02] It is said that under the Knights, this was the one day in the year when the Maltese were allowed to hunt and eat wild rabbit, which was otherwise reserved for the hunting pleasures of the Knights.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The close connection between Mnarja and rabbit stew (Maltese: *"fenkata"*) remains strong today.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Isle of MTV is a one-day music festival produced and broadcast on an annual basis by MTV.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The festival has been arranged annually in Malta since 2007, with major pop artists performing each year.
[src:malta/malta-p02] 2012 saw the performances of worldwide acclaimed artists Flo Rida, Nelly Furtado and Will.i.am.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Over 50,000 people attended, which marked the biggest attendance so far.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Malta International Fireworks Festival has been arranged annually in the Grand Harbour of Valletta since 2003.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Maltese architecture has been influenced by many different Mediterranean cultures and British architecture over its history.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The first settlers on the island constructed Ġgantija, one of the oldest manmade freestanding structures in the world.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Neolithic temple builders (3800–2500 BC) endowed the numerous temples of Malta and Gozo with intricate bas-relief designs.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Roman period introduced highly decorative mosaic floors, marble colonnades, and classical statuary, remnants of which are beautifully preserved and presented in the Roman Domus, a country villa just outside the walls of Mdina.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The early Christian frescoes that decorate the catacombs beneath Malta reveal a propensity for eastern, Byzantine tastes.
[src:malta/malta-p02] These tastes continued to inform the endeavours of medieval Maltese artists, but they were increasingly influenced by the Romanesque and Southern French Gothic movements.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Towards the end of the 15th century, Maltese artists, like their counterparts in Sicily, came under the influence of the School of Antonello da Messina, which introduced Renaissance ideals and concepts to the decorative arts in Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The artistic heritage of Malta blossomed under the Knights of St.
[src:malta/malta-p02] John, who brought Italian and Flemish Mannerist painters to decorate their palaces and the churches of these islands, most notably, Matteo Perez d'Aleccio, whose works appear in the Magisterial Palace and in the Conventual Church of St.
[src:malta/malta-p02] John in Valletta, and Filippo Paladini, who was active in Malta from 1590 to 1595.
[src:malta/malta-p02] For many years, Mannerism continued to inform the tastes and ideals of local Maltese artists.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The arrival in Malta of Caravaggio, who painted at least seven works during his 15-month stay on these islands, further revolutionised local art.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Two of Caravaggio's most notable works, *The Beheading of Saint John the Baptist* and *Saint Jerome Writing*, are on display in the Conventual Church of St.
[src:malta/malta-p02] His legacy is evident in the works of local artists Giulio Cassarino and Stefano Erardi.
[src:malta/malta-p02] However, the Baroque movement that followed was destined to have the most enduring impact on Maltese art and architecture.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The vault paintings of the Calabrese artist Mattia Preti transformed the Conventual Church St.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Melchior Gafà emerged as one of the top Baroque sculptors of the Roman School.
[src:malta/malta-p02] During the 17th and 18th centuries, Neapolitan and Rococo influences emerged in the works of the Italian painters Luca Giordano and Francesco Solimena, and these developments can be seen in the work of their Maltese contemporaries such as Gio Nicola Buhagiar and Francesco Zahra.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Rococo movement was greatly enhanced by the relocation to Malta of Antoine de Favray, who assumed the position of court painter to Grand Master Pinto in 1744.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Romanticism, tempered by the naturalism introduced to Malta by Giuseppe Calì, informed the "salon" artists of the early 20th century, including Edward and Robert Caruana Dingli.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Parliament established the National School of Art in the 1920s.
[src:malta/malta-p02] During the reconstruction period that followed the Second World War, the emergence of the "Modern Art Group", whose members included Josef Kalleya, George Preca, Anton Inglott, Emvin Cremona, Frank Portelli, Antoine Camilleri, Gabriel Caruana and Esprit Barthet greatly enhanced the local art scene.
[src:malta/malta-p02] This group came together forming an influential pressure group known as the Modern Art Group, which played a leading role in the renewal of Maltese art.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Most of Malta's modern artists have in fact studied in art institutions in England, or on the continent, leading to a diversity of artistic expression that has remained characteristic of contemporary Maltese art.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In Valletta, the National Museum of Fine Arts featured work from artists such as H.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In 2018 the national collection of fine arts was put on display in the new National Museum of Art, MUŻA, at Auberge d'Italie in Valletta.
[src:malta/malta-p02] While Maltese music today is largely Western, traditional Maltese music includes what is known as *għana*.
[src:malta/malta-p02] This consists of background folk guitar music, while a few people, generally men, take it in turns to argue a point in a sing-song voice.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Music plays an important part in Maltese culture as each locality parades its own band club, on various occasions these being multiple per locality, and function to establish the thematic musical background to the various village feasts.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Malta Philharmonic Orchestra is recognised as Malta's foremost musical institution and is notable for being called to participate in important state events.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Documented Maltese literature is over 200 years old.
[src:malta/malta-p02] However, a recently unearthed love ballad testifies to literary activity in the local tongue from the Medieval period.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Malta followed a Romantic literary tradition, culminating in the works of Dun Karm Psaila, Malta's national poet.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Subsequent writers like Ruzar Briffa and Karmenu Vassallo tried to estrange themselves from the rigidity of formal themes and versification.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The next generation of writers, including Karl Schembri and Immanuel Mifsud, widened the tracks further, especially in prose and poetry.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The most widely read and financially the strongest newspapers are published by Allied Newspapers Ltd., mainly *The Times of Malta* (27 percent) and its Sunday edition *The Sunday Times of Malta* (51.6 percent).
[src:malta/malta-p02] Due to bilingualism half of the newspapers are published in English and the other half in Maltese.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Sunday newspaper *It-Torċa* ("The Torch") published by a subsidiary of the General Workers' Union, is the widest Maltese language paper.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Its sister paper, *L-Orizzont* ("The Horizon"), is the Maltese daily with the biggest circulation.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There is a high number of daily or weekly newspapers—one for every 28,000 people.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Advertising, sales, and subsidies are the three main methods of financing.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There are nine terrestrial television channels in Malta: TVM, TVMNews+, Parliament TV, One, NET Television, Smash Television, F Living, TVMSport+ and Xejk.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The state and political parties subsidise most of the funding of these channels.
[src:malta/malta-p02] TVM, TVMNews+, and Parliament TV are operated by Public Broadcasting Services, the national broadcaster, and members of the EBU.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Media.link Communications Ltd., the owner of NET Television, and One Productions Ltd., the owner of One, are affiliated with the Nationalist and Labour parties, respectively.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Malta Broadcasting Authority has authority to supervise all local broadcasting stations and ensures their compliance with legal and licence obligations as well as the preservation of due impartiality.
[src:malta/malta-p02] The Malta Communications Authority reported that there were 147,896 pay TV subscriptions active at the end of 2012.
[src:malta/malta-p02] For reference the 2011 census counts 139,583 households in Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Other European television networks can be received via satellite.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Maltese cuisine shows strong Sicilian and Italian influences as well as influences of English, Spanish, Maghrebin and Provençal cuisines.
[src:malta/malta-p02] A number of regional variations can be noted as well as seasonal variations associated with the seasonal availability of produce and Christian feasts (such as Lent, Easter and Christmas).
[src:malta/malta-p02] Food has been important historically in the development of a national identity, in particular the traditional *fenkata* (i.e., the eating of stewed or fried rabbit).
[src:malta/malta-p02] Potatoes are a staple of the Maltese diet as well.
[src:malta/malta-p02] A number of grapes are endemic to Malta, including Girgentina and Ġellewża.
[src:malta/malta-p02] There is a strong wine industry, with significant production of wines using these native grapes, as well as locally grown grapes of other more common varietals.
[src:malta/malta-p02] A number of wines have achieved Protected Designation of Origin, with wines produced from grapes cultivated in Malta and Gozo designated as "DOK" wines, that is *Denominazzjoni ta' l-Oriġini Kontrollata*.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Football (soccer) is one of the most popular sports in Malta.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Other popular sports include boċċi, horse racing, gostra, regatta, water polo, clay pigeon shooting, and motorsports.
[src:malta/malta-p02] In 2018 Malta hosted its first Esports tournament, 'Supernova CS:GO Malta', a Counter-Strike: Global Offensive tournament.
[src:malta/malta-p02] Also since 2018, Malta has become the primary location for hosting the ESL Pro League.
[src:malta/mt] Since 1 December 2017, it is possible to register .mt domains directly at the second level, such as myname.mt.
[src:malta/mt] Registration is possible at the third level under a number of second level domain names.
